var SIE_QUESTIONS_SERIES7 = [{"id":"series7-s7-q-037","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"American Depositary Receipts (ADRs) allow U.S. investors to:","choices":{"A":"Trade foreign stocks directly on foreign exchanges","B":"Purchase shares of foreign companies in U.S. dollars on U.S. exchanges","C":"Avoid all currency risk when investing internationally","D":"Bypass SEC registration requirements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"ADRs enable U.S. investors to purchase shares of foreign companies in U.S. dollars on U.S. exchanges. While trading is in dollars, investors still face currency risk because the underlying foreign shares are valued in foreign currency. ADRs do not bypass SEC requirements - they have varying levels of SEC registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series7-s7-q-054","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A California resident purchases a municipal bond issued by the state of California. The interest is most likely:","choices":{"A":"Taxable at federal, state, and local levels","B":"Exempt from federal tax only","C":"Exempt from California state tax only","D":"Exempt from both federal and California state tax"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Municipal bond interest is generally exempt from federal income tax. When a resident purchases a bond from their home state, the interest is also typically exempt from that state's income tax - making it \"double tax-free\" (or triple tax-free if local taxes also apply).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-s7-q-059","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a put option. This investor has:","choices":{"A":"The right to buy the underlying stock","B":"The obligation to sell the underlying stock","C":"The right to sell the underlying stock","D":"The obligation to buy the underlying stock"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The buyer of a put option has the right to sell the underlying stock at the strike price. Put buyers are bearish - they profit when the stock price falls below the strike price. The put seller has the obligation to buy if the option is exercised.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["put-options"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-001","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"In a corporate liquidation, common stockholders are paid:","choices":{"A":"Before preferred stockholders","B":"After secured creditors but before bondholders","C":"After all creditors and preferred stockholders","D":"Equally with bondholders"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Common stockholders have a residual claim on assets, meaning they are paid last in liquidation - after secured creditors, unsecured creditors, bondholders, and preferred stockholders. This higher risk is why common stock typically offers greater growth potential.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-002","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns 200 shares of XYZ Corporation. At the annual meeting, four directors are being elected using cumulative voting. How many total votes does this investor have?","choices":{"A":"200 votes","B":"400 votes","C":"600 votes","D":"800 votes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"With cumulative voting, the total votes equal the number of shares multiplied by the number of positions being elected. This investor has 200 shares x 4 directors = 800 total votes, which could all be cast for a single candidate or distributed among multiple candidates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-003","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A corporation has 10 million authorized shares, 8 million issued shares, and 1 million shares held as treasury stock. How many shares are outstanding?","choices":{"A":"10 million","B":"9 million","C":"8 million","D":"7 million"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Outstanding shares equal issued shares minus treasury stock: 8 million - 1 million = 7 million outstanding shares. Authorized shares represent the maximum that could be issued but are not part of this calculation. Treasury stock has been repurchased and is no longer outstanding.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-004","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock has a record date of Wednesday, March 12. When is the ex-dividend date?","choices":{"A":"Monday, March 10","B":"Tuesday, March 11","C":"Wednesday, March 12","D":"Thursday, March 13"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The ex-dividend date is one business day before the record date. With a Wednesday record date, the ex-dividend date is Tuesday. This allows trades made before the ex-date to settle by the record date under T+1 settlement rules.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-005","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns 400 shares of ABC stock at $75 per share. The company declares a 3-for-1 stock split. After the split, the investor has:","choices":{"A":"400 shares at $75","B":"1,200 shares at $75","C":"1,200 shares at $25","D":"133 shares at $225"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a 3-for-1 split, shares triple and price is divided by 3. The investor receives 400 x 3 = 1,200 shares. The price adjusts to $75 / 3 = $25. Total value remains $30,000 (400 x $75 = 1,200 x $25).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-006","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company trading at $40 per share declares a 25% stock dividend. What is the adjusted stock price?","choices":{"A":"$30","B":"$32","C":"$35","D":"$50"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For stock dividends, the adjusted price = original price / (1 + dividend percentage). So $40 / 1.25 = $32. The shareholder has 25% more shares at 80% of the original price, maintaining the same total value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-007","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"ABC Corporation has $6 cumulative preferred stock outstanding. The company missed dividend payments for 3 years and now wants to pay common stockholders a dividend. What must happen first?","choices":{"A":"Common shareholders must approve the preferred dividend","B":"The company must pay $18 per share to preferred stockholders","C":"The company must issue new preferred shares","D":"Preferred stockholders must convert to common stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"With cumulative preferred, dividends in arrears must be paid before any common dividends. The company missed 3 years of $6 annual dividends, so $18 per share (3 x $6) must be paid to preferred stockholders before common shareholders receive anything.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-008","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor holds convertible preferred stock with a conversion ratio of 5:1. The preferred stock is trading at $80, and the common stock is at $18. The parity price of the preferred is:","choices":{"A":"$16","B":"$80","C":"$90","D":"$100"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Parity price is the value of the common stock received upon conversion. With a 5:1 ratio and common at $18, parity = 5 x $18 = $90. Since parity ($90) exceeds the preferred market price ($80), conversion would be profitable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-009","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"If market interest rates increase significantly, what would most likely happen to the price of outstanding preferred stock?","choices":{"A":"The price would increase","B":"The price would decrease","C":"The price would remain unchanged","D":"The dividend would increase automatically"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Preferred stock prices have an inverse relationship with interest rates, similar to bonds. When rates rise, the fixed dividend becomes less attractive compared to new higher-yielding investments, causing the preferred stock price to fall.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["preferred-stock","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-010","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company announces a rights offering where shareholders need 5 rights to purchase one new share at $25. The stock is currently trading cum-rights at $32. What is the value of one right?","choices":{"A":"$1.00","B":"$1.17","C":"$1.40","D":"$7.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using the cum-rights formula: Value = (Market Price - Subscription Price) / (Rights Needed + 1). Value = ($32 - $25) / (5 + 1) = $7 / 6 = $1.17 (rounded). The +1 accounts for the fact that the stock price includes the right's value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["rights-warrants"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-011","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following is a characteristic of warrants but NOT of rights?","choices":{"A":"They allow purchase of common stock","B":"They have an exercise price","C":"They typically have a life of several years","D":"They can be traded on exchanges"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The key distinguishing feature is duration. Warrants typically have lives of 2-10 years (or longer), while rights are short-term instruments that expire within 30-45 days. Both allow stock purchases, have exercise prices, and can trade on exchanges.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["rights-warrants"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-012","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor receives rights in a rights offering but does not want to purchase additional shares. What is the BEST course of action?","choices":{"A":"Let the rights expire","B":"Sell the rights on the open market","C":"Convert the rights to warrants","D":"Return the rights to the company"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Rights have monetary value that can be captured by selling them on the open market. Letting rights expire wastes their value. Rights cannot be converted to warrants, and companies don't accept returned rights.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["rights-warrants"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-013","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A foreign company wants to list its ADRs on the New York Stock Exchange and raise capital through a U.S. public offering. Which ADR level is required?","choices":{"A":"Level I","B":"Level II","C":"Level III","D":"Any level can raise capital"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Only Level III ADRs allow foreign companies to raise capital in U.S. markets through public offerings. Level I trades OTC and cannot raise capital. Level II can list on exchanges but cannot raise new capital. Level III requires full SEC registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-014","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns ADRs of a British company. The underlying shares are unchanged in British pounds, but the pound weakens 10% against the U.S. dollar. What happens to the ADR value?","choices":{"A":"It increases by approximately 10%","B":"It decreases by approximately 10%","C":"It remains unchanged","D":"It converts to British pounds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Currency risk affects ADR values. When the foreign currency (pound) weakens against the dollar, the ADR loses value even if the underlying shares remain stable. A 10% decline in the pound would cause approximately a 10% decline in the ADR value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch1-015","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following is a characteristic of unsponsored ADRs?","choices":{"A":"They can only trade on the NYSE","B":"They are created with the foreign company's involvement","C":"Multiple depositary banks may issue them","D":"They require full SEC registration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Unsponsored ADRs are created without the foreign company's involvement, which means multiple depositary banks may independently create ADRs for the same company. They trade OTC (not on major exchanges), don't require SEC registration, and offer limited shareholder services.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["adrs"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-001","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond with a 5% coupon is trading at 97. This bond is selling at:","choices":{"A":"A premium because the coupon is above market rates","B":"A discount because the market price is below par","C":"Par value","D":"A premium because 97 is close to 100"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A bond quoted at 97 means it trades at 97% of par value, or $970 for a $1,000 bond. Since this is below par ($1,000), the bond is selling at a discount. This indicates market interest rates have risen above the 5% coupon rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-002","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A corporate bond pays 6% annual interest. The last coupon was paid on April 1, and the bond is sold on June 15. Using the 30/360 convention, what is the accrued interest?","choices":{"A":"$10.00","B":"$12.50","C":"$15.00","D":"$17.50"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using 30/360: April (30 days) + May (30 days) + June 1-15 (15 days) = 75 days. Accrued interest = ($60 annual interest / 360) x 75 days = $0.1667 x 75 = $12.50.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-003","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"If market interest rates decrease, what happens to outstanding bond prices?","choices":{"A":"Bond prices decrease","B":"Bond prices increase","C":"Bond prices remain unchanged","D":"Only premium bond prices change"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bond prices and interest rates have an inverse relationship. When market rates decrease, existing bonds with higher coupon rates become more valuable, causing their prices to increase. This is a fundamental concept tested frequently on the Series 7 exam.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["bond-pricing","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond with a 6% coupon is trading at $1,100. The current yield is:","choices":{"A":"5.45%","B":"6.00%","C":"6.60%","D":"7.27%"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Current yield = Annual Interest / Market Price. Annual interest is $60 (6% x $1,000 par). Current yield = $60 / $1,100 = 5.45%. Since the bond is at a premium, the current yield is less than the coupon rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-005","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"For a bond trading at a discount, which yield is the highest?","choices":{"A":"Nominal yield (coupon)","B":"Current yield","C":"Yield to maturity","D":"Yield to call"},"answer":"D","explanation":"For discount bonds, the yield order from lowest to highest is: Coupon < Current Yield < YTM < YTC. Yield to call is highest because the investor receives the gain (from discount to call price) over a shorter time period than maturity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An inverted yield curve indicates:","choices":{"A":"Strong economic growth is expected","B":"Short-term rates are higher than long-term rates","C":"Long-term bonds are riskier than short-term bonds","D":"The Federal Reserve is lowering interest rates"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An inverted (negative) yield curve occurs when short-term interest rates are higher than long-term rates. This unusual condition is often considered a predictor of economic recession, as investors expect future rates to decline.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields","interest-rates","economic-indicators"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"In a corporate liquidation, which of the following would be paid first?","choices":{"A":"Common stockholders","B":"Subordinated debenture holders","C":"Preferred stockholders","D":"Mortgage bondholders"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Mortgage bondholders are secured creditors with first claim on specific collateral. The liquidation order is: secured creditors (mortgage bonds), unsecured creditors (debentures), subordinated debt, preferred stock, then common stock.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A convertible bond has a par value of $1,000 and converts into 20 shares of common stock. If the stock is trading at $60, what is the bond's conversion value?","choices":{"A":"$500","B":"$1,000","C":"$1,200","D":"$1,500"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Conversion value = Conversion ratio x Current stock price. With a 20:1 ratio and stock at $60: 20 shares x $60 = $1,200. Since conversion value ($1,200) exceeds par ($1,000), conversion may be advantageous.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-010","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond rated Ba1 by Moody's would be classified as:","choices":{"A":"Investment grade","B":"High quality","C":"Speculative grade (junk)","D":"In default"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Moody's Ba1 (equivalent to S&P's BB+) is the highest speculative-grade rating. Investment grade includes Baa3/BBB- and above. Anything rated Ba1/BB+ or below is considered high-yield or \"junk\" and carries substantial default risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-ratings","corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-011","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Call provisions in a bond primarily benefit:","choices":{"A":"The bondholder","B":"The issuer","C":"Both equally","D":"Neither party"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Call provisions benefit the issuer by allowing them to refinance debt when interest rates fall. The issuer can call high-coupon bonds and reissue at lower rates. This is disadvantageous for bondholders who lose their higher-yielding investment and face reinvestment risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-012","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which type of bond has NO reinvestment risk?","choices":{"A":"High-coupon bonds","B":"Callable bonds","C":"Zero-coupon bonds","D":"Bonds with sinking funds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Zero-coupon bonds have no reinvestment risk because they pay no periodic interest. There are no coupon payments to reinvest at potentially lower rates. All return comes from the difference between the discounted purchase price and par value at maturity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-013","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which bond would have the GREATEST interest rate risk?","choices":{"A":"5-year bond with 8% coupon","B":"5-year bond with 4% coupon","C":"20-year bond with 8% coupon","D":"20-year bond with 4% coupon"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Interest rate risk is highest with longer maturities and lower coupon rates. The 20-year bond with a 4% coupon has both the longest maturity and lowest coupon, making it most sensitive to interest rate changes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch2-014","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A sinking fund provision requires the issuer to:","choices":{"A":"Pay all bondholders at once","B":"Retire a portion of the bond issue periodically","C":"Increase coupon payments over time","D":"Convert bonds to stock"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A sinking fund requires the issuer to retire a portion of the bond issue before maturity, either by purchasing bonds in the open market or calling them by lottery. This reduces default risk but creates refunding risk for bondholders whose bonds may be called early.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-001","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which Treasury security is sold at a discount and does NOT pay periodic interest?","choices":{"A":"Treasury Bills","B":"Treasury Notes","C":"Treasury Bonds","D":"Treasury TIPS"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Treasury Bills (T-Bills) are sold at a discount to face value and do not pay coupon interest. The investor's return is the difference between the purchase price and the face value received at maturity. T-Notes, T-Bonds, and TIPS all pay semiannual interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-002","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A Treasury Inflation-Protected Security (TIPS) has an original principal of $1,000 and a 2% coupon rate. If inflation causes the principal to adjust to $1,050, what is the next semiannual interest payment?","choices":{"A":"$10.00","B":"$10.50","C":"$20.00","D":"$21.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"TIPS pay interest based on the adjusted principal. With a 2% annual coupon rate, the semiannual rate is 1%. On an adjusted principal of $1,050, the semiannual payment is $1,050 x 1% = $10.50.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-003","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Treasury STRIPS are:","choices":{"A":"Issued directly by the U.S. Treasury through TreasuryDirect","B":"Created by broker-dealers who separate Treasury securities into components","C":"Guaranteed by government-sponsored enterprises","D":"Exempt from federal income tax"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Treasury STRIPS are NOT issued directly by the Treasury. They are created when broker-dealers \"strip\" Treasury notes or bonds into their individual interest and principal components. Each component then trades as a separate zero-coupon security. STRIPS are taxable at the federal level.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"In a Treasury auction, what is the maximum amount an individual can bid non-competitively?","choices":{"A":"$1 million","B":"$5 million","C":"$10 million","D":"$35 million"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Non-competitive bids in Treasury auctions are limited to $10 million per auction. Non-competitive bidders agree to accept the rate determined at auction and are guaranteed to receive securities. Competitive bids are limited to 35% of the offering amount.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds","primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-005","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following is backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government?","choices":{"A":"Fannie Mae securities","B":"Freddie Mac securities","C":"Ginnie Mae securities","D":"Federal Home Loan Bank securities"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Ginnie Mae (GNMA) is the ONLY mortgage-related entity backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government. It is a government-owned corporation within HUD. Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, and Federal Home Loan Banks are government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) with only implicit government backing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac are:","choices":{"A":"Government agencies backed by the U.S. Treasury","B":"Government-sponsored enterprises under FHFA conservatorship","C":"Divisions of the Department of Housing and Urban Development","D":"Private companies with no government relationship"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac are government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs), not government agencies. They have been operating under FHFA (Federal Housing Finance Agency) conservatorship since September 2008. They have implicit but not explicit government backing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Agency securities are considered \"Exempted Securities\" under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. This means they are:","choices":{"A":"Exempt from all federal securities laws","B":"Exempt from registration requirements but not antifraud provisions","C":"Only available to institutional investors","D":"Guaranteed against loss by the federal government"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Agency securities are exempt from SEC registration requirements, meaning they can be sold without a prospectus. However, they are NOT exempt from antifraud provisions - misleading statements about agency securities are still illegal. This status applies to the securities, not to credit risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"If interest rates decline significantly, which of the following is MOST likely to occur with mortgage-backed pass-through securities?","choices":{"A":"Prepayments will decrease as homeowners hold their mortgages","B":"Prepayments will increase as homeowners refinance","C":"The securities will be called by the issuer","D":"Interest payments to investors will increase"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When interest rates fall, homeowners are more likely to refinance their mortgages at lower rates. This causes prepayments to increase, returning principal to MBS investors sooner than expected. This is prepayment risk - investors must reinvest the returned principal at lower prevailing rates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which CMO tranche has the MOST predictable cash flows and the LOWEST yield?","choices":{"A":"Companion tranche","B":"Z-tranche","C":"PAC tranche","D":"TAC tranche"},"answer":"C","explanation":"PAC (Planned Amortization Class) tranches have the most predictable cash flows because they are protected from both prepayment and extension risk by companion tranches. Because of this lower risk, PAC tranches offer the lowest yield among CMO tranches.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-010","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A companion tranche in a CMO structure:","choices":{"A":"Has the most predictable cash flows","B":"Is protected from prepayment risk by PAC tranches","C":"Absorbs excess prepayments to protect PAC and TAC tranches","D":"Receives payments before all other tranches"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Companion (support) tranches absorb the prepayment and extension risk that PAC and TAC tranches are protected from. When prepayments are higher than expected, companion tranches receive the excess. When prepayments are lower, companion tranche payments slow down. This makes them the most volatile but highest-yielding CMO tranches.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-011","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Interest-only (IO) CMO tranches typically INCREASE in value when:","choices":{"A":"Interest rates fall and prepayments increase","B":"Interest rates rise and prepayments decrease","C":"The underlying mortgages default","D":"The companion tranche is retired"},"answer":"B","explanation":"IO tranches receive only interest payments. When interest rates rise, fewer homeowners refinance, meaning mortgages last longer and more total interest is paid. This increases the value of IO tranches. This is counterintuitive because most bonds lose value when rates rise, but IOs behave differently.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-013","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A customer asks about a money market instrument used to finance international trade. The instrument is guaranteed by a bank. Which security is being described?","choices":{"A":"Commercial paper","B":"Repurchase agreement","C":"Bankers' acceptance","D":"Negotiable CD"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Bankers' acceptances (BAs) are time drafts used primarily to finance international trade (importing and exporting). When a bank \"accepts\" the draft, it guarantees payment at maturity. BAs typically have maturities of 30 to 180 days.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-014","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which money market instrument is the MOST liquid?","choices":{"A":"Commercial paper","B":"Negotiable CDs","C":"Repurchase agreements","D":"Bankers' acceptances"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Repurchase agreements (repos) are the most liquid money market instruments. They can have maturities as short as overnight and are collateralized by government securities, making them very safe and easy to trade. They are heavily used by dealers and the Federal Reserve.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch3-015","section":"Economics","stem":"The federal funds rate is:","choices":{"A":"Set directly by the Federal Reserve Board","B":"The rate banks charge each other for overnight loans","C":"The discount rate charged by Federal Reserve Banks","D":"The rate on 30-year Treasury bonds"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The federal funds rate is the interest rate banks charge each other for overnight loans to meet reserve requirements. The FOMC sets a target range for this rate and uses open market operations to keep the actual rate within the target, but the rate itself is determined by supply and demand in the interbank market.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["interest-rates","frb"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-001","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor in the 32% federal tax bracket is considering a municipal bond yielding 3.5%. What is the tax-equivalent yield?","choices":{"A":"4.25%","B":"4.76%","C":"5.15%","D":"5.47%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax-Equivalent Yield = Municipal Yield / (1 - Tax Rate) = 3.5% / (1 - 0.32) = 3.5% / 0.68 = 5.15%. This means a taxable bond would need to yield 5.15% to equal the after-tax return of this 3.5% municipal bond.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-yields"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-002","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following municipal bonds would be subject to the Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT)?","choices":{"A":"A school district general obligation bond","B":"A state highway revenue bond","C":"A private activity bond financing an airport","D":"A city water utility bond"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Private activity bonds - those used to finance private enterprises like airports, stadiums, and industrial development - may be subject to AMT. Regular municipal bonds for public purposes like schools, highways, and water utilities are not subject to AMT.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-003","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A California resident purchases a municipal bond issued by the State of New York. The interest income is:","choices":{"A":"Exempt from federal, California state, and New York state taxes","B":"Exempt from federal tax only","C":"Exempt from federal and New York state taxes only","D":"Fully taxable at all levels"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Municipal bond interest is generally exempt from federal tax. However, state tax exemption typically applies only to residents of the issuing state. A California resident buying a New York bond would pay California state tax on the interest but not federal tax.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An unlimited tax general obligation bond is backed by:","choices":{"A":"Revenue from a specific project","B":"The issuer's ability to levy property taxes without limit","C":"Insurance from a bond insurance company","D":"Federal government guarantees"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Unlimited tax GO bonds are backed by the issuer's full faith and credit, including the power to levy ad valorem (property) taxes without any statutory limit on the tax rate. This is the strongest municipal bond security pledge.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-005","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following is a factor used to analyze the creditworthiness of a general obligation bond?","choices":{"A":"The rate covenant","B":"The flow of funds","C":"Debt per capita","D":"The additional bonds test"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Debt per capita (total debt divided by population) is a key metric for analyzing GO bonds because it measures the debt burden on taxpayers. Rate covenant, flow of funds, and additional bonds test are all revenue bond concepts, not GO bond analysis factors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A \"double-barreled\" municipal bond is:","choices":{"A":"A bond with two different maturity dates","B":"A bond backed by both a revenue source and a GO pledge","C":"A bond that pays interest twice annually","D":"A bond issued by two different municipalities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A double-barreled bond has two sources of security: a specific revenue stream AND the full faith and credit (GO pledge) of the issuer. This dual backing typically results in higher credit quality than a single-source bond.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Under a net revenue pledge for a municipal revenue bond, what is paid FIRST from collected revenues?","choices":{"A":"Debt service","B":"Debt service reserve fund","C":"Operation and maintenance expenses","D":"Sinking fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under a net revenue pledge (the most common type), operation and maintenance (O&M) expenses are paid first. Debt service is paid second, from the \"net\" revenues remaining after O&M. This differs from a gross revenue pledge, where debt service is paid first.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"The purpose of an additional bonds test in a revenue bond indenture is to:","choices":{"A":"Ensure the issuer maintains adequate insurance","B":"Require voter approval for new bonds","C":"Protect existing bondholders from dilution of their security","D":"Set minimum user fees for the facility"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The additional bonds test protects existing bondholders by requiring the issuer to demonstrate that revenues will be sufficient to cover both existing and new debt service before issuing additional bonds backed by the same revenue source.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which type of revenue bond indenture is MORE favorable to bondholders?","choices":{"A":"Open-end indenture","B":"Closed-end indenture","C":"Net revenue pledge","D":"Both A and C"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A closed-end indenture is more favorable to bondholders because any new bonds issued must be subordinate (junior) to the original bonds. In an open-end indenture, new bonds have equal claim to revenues (pari passu), diluting existing bondholders' security.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-010","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A hospital revenue bond is backed by:","choices":{"A":"Property taxes from the surrounding area","B":"The full faith and credit of the state","C":"Patient fees and other hospital revenues","D":"Federal Medicare guarantee"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hospital revenue bonds are backed by the hospital's revenues - patient fees, insurance reimbursements, and other income generated by hospital operations. They are not backed by taxes or government guarantees.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-011","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor researching a municipal bond should find the official statement on:","choices":{"A":"The SEC's EDGAR database","B":"The MSRB's EMMA website","C":"The FINRA BrokerCheck website","D":"The issuer's investor relations page only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"EMMA (Electronic Municipal Market Access) is the MSRB's free online platform where investors can access official statements, trade data, continuing disclosure documents, and credit ratings for municipal securities. EDGAR is for corporate filings, not municipal bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds","msrb"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-012","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A municipal bond rated 'Ba1' by Moody's would be considered:","choices":{"A":"Investment grade","B":"Speculative grade (high-yield)","C":"Unrated","D":"Insured"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Ba1 is below investment grade (which starts at Baa3 for Moody's). Bonds rated Ba or below are considered speculative grade, also called high-yield or \"junk\" bonds. They carry higher default risk but offer higher yields to compensate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-013","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"The purpose of municipal bond insurance is to:","choices":{"A":"Protect against interest rate risk","B":"Guarantee timely payment of principal and interest if the issuer defaults","C":"Insure the bondholder against market value losses","D":"Provide FDIC coverage for the investment"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Municipal bond insurance provides a guarantee that if the issuer defaults, the insurance company will make timely payments of principal and interest to bondholders. It does not protect against market value changes or interest rate risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-014","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Under MSRB Rule G-37, if a municipal finance professional makes a political contribution to an issuer official, the dealer is banned from negotiated underwriting with that issuer for:","choices":{"A":"6 months","B":"1 year","C":"2 years","D":"5 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Rule G-37 imposes a two-year ban on negotiated underwriting business with an issuer if a dealer or municipal finance professional makes a political contribution to an official of that issuer (beyond the $250 de minimis exception for officials one can vote for).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-015","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The MSRB (Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board):","choices":{"A":"Writes and enforces rules for municipal securities dealers","B":"Writes rules for municipal securities dealers but does not enforce them","C":"Only regulates municipal advisors, not dealers","D":"Is a division of the Federal Reserve"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The MSRB writes rules for municipal securities dealers and municipal advisors, but it does NOT have enforcement authority. Enforcement is carried out by FINRA (for broker-dealers) and the SEC (for municipal advisors and overall oversight).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-016","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Under MSRB Rule G-17, an underwriter in a negotiated municipal offering must disclose to the issuer:","choices":{"A":"The names of all potential investors","B":"That the relationship is arm's-length, not fiduciary","C":"The underwriter's quarterly financial statements","D":"The identities of other issuers the underwriter has worked with"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Rule G-17 requires underwriters to clearly disclose that their relationship with the issuer is arm's-length (not fiduciary) and that they have their own interests to consider. Underwriters must also disclose conflicts of interest and material risks of recommended financing structures.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch4-017","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The de minimis exception under MSRB Rule G-37 allows a municipal finance professional to contribute up to what amount per election to officials they can vote for?","choices":{"A":"$100","B":"$250","C":"$500","D":"$1,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The de minimis exception under Rule G-37 permits municipal finance professionals to contribute up to $250 per election to officials for whom they are entitled to vote without triggering the two-year ban on municipal securities business.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-001","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A mutual fund has total assets of $200 million, liabilities of $2 million, and 10 million shares outstanding. What is the NAV per share?","choices":{"A":"$19.80","B":"$20.00","C":"$20.20","D":"$22.00"},"answer":"A","explanation":"NAV = (Assets - Liabilities) / Shares Outstanding = ($200M - $2M) / 10M = $198M / 10M = $19.80 per share.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-002","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor places a mutual fund purchase order at 3:30 PM ET on Tuesday. At what price will the order execute?","choices":{"A":"Monday's closing NAV","B":"Tuesday's opening NAV","C":"Tuesday's closing NAV","D":"Wednesday's closing NAV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Mutual funds use forward pricing. Orders placed before the 4:00 PM ET cutoff execute at that day's closing NAV.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-003","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which of the following characteristics applies to a Unit Investment Trust (UIT)?","choices":{"A":"Actively managed portfolio","B":"No termination date","C":"Fixed portfolio that does not change","D":"Board of directors and investment adviser required"},"answer":"C","explanation":"UITs hold a fixed portfolio of securities that is established at creation and does not change. They are unmanaged, have a specified termination date, and do not have a board of directors or investment adviser.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uits"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-004","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A fund has an NAV of $12.00 and a 4% front-end sales charge. What is the Public Offering Price (POP)?","choices":{"A":"$12.00","B":"$12.48","C":"$12.50","D":"$12.96"},"answer":"C","explanation":"POP = NAV / (100% - Sales Charge %) = $12.00 / 0.96 = $12.50. The sales charge is based on the POP, not the NAV.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-005","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"What is the maximum total 12b-1 fee that can be charged by a mutual fund?","choices":{"A":"0.25%","B":"0.75%","C":"1.00%","D":"8.50%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"12b-1 fees are capped at 1.00% of fund assets annually (0.75% for distribution fees + 0.25% for service fees).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-006","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor has $48,000 invested in a fund. The $50,000 breakpoint offers 4.25% load. She invests an additional $5,000. Under rights of accumulation, what sales charge applies?","choices":{"A":"The 5.00% rate for purchases under $50,000","B":"The 4.25% rate because combined value exceeds $50,000","C":"No sales charge","D":"The average of 5.00% and 4.25%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Rights of accumulation allow investors to combine their current account value ($48,000) with the new purchase ($5,000) to qualify for a breakpoint.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-007","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A closed-end fund has an NAV of $25.00 and is trading at $22.50. The fund is trading at:","choices":{"A":"A 10% premium","B":"A 10% discount","C":"A 11.1% premium","D":"A 11.1% discount"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Discount = (NAV - Market Price) / NAV = ($25.00 - $22.50) / $25.00 = 10% discount. The fund is trading below NAV.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["closed-end-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-008","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which type of fund is MOST likely to have the lowest expense ratio?","choices":{"A":"Actively managed growth fund","B":"Index ETF","C":"Sector-specific mutual fund","D":"International equity fund"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Index ETFs typically have the lowest expense ratios because they are passively managed.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-009","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"To qualify as a Regulated Investment Company and avoid taxation at the fund level, a mutual fund must distribute what percentage of its net investment income?","choices":{"A":"75%","B":"80%","C":"90%","D":"100%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under IRC Subchapter M, a fund must distribute at least 90% of its net investment income to qualify for conduit tax treatment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-010","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor purchased mutual fund shares 6 months ago. She receives a capital gains distribution from the fund. This distribution is taxed as:","choices":{"A":"Short-term capital gains because she held shares less than one year","B":"Long-term capital gains regardless of her holding period","C":"Ordinary income","D":"Not taxable until shares are sold"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Capital gains distributions from mutual funds are always taxed as long-term capital gains to shareholders, regardless of how long the shareholder has owned the fund shares.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-011","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"When a mutual fund shareholder reinvests dividends, the reinvestment occurs at:","choices":{"A":"The Public Offering Price (POP)","B":"Net Asset Value (NAV)","C":"A 5% discount to NAV","D":"The previous day's closing price"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Dividend and capital gains reinvestments in mutual funds occur at the Net Asset Value (NAV), with no sales charge applied.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-012","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A customer signs a Letter of Intent (LOI) to reach a breakpoint. What is the maximum time period allowed to complete the investment?","choices":{"A":"6 months","B":"12 months","C":"13 months","D":"18 months"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A Letter of Intent allows an investor 13 months to complete the investment necessary to reach a breakpoint.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-013","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which share class would be MOST appropriate for an investor planning to hold a fund for 10+ years with a $100,000 investment?","choices":{"A":"Class A shares","B":"Class B shares","C":"Class C shares","D":"All share classes are equally appropriate"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Class A shares are most appropriate for large, long-term investments due to breakpoints and lower ongoing 12b-1 fees.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-014","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"What percentage of a mutual fund's board of directors must be independent (non-interested)?","choices":{"A":"At least 25%","B":"At least 40%","C":"At least 51%","D":"100%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the Investment Company Act of 1940, at least 40% of a mutual fund's board of directors must be independent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-company-act","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-015","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor purchases shares of a municipal bond fund. Which of the following distributions would be TAXABLE?","choices":{"A":"Interest income from municipal bonds","B":"Capital gains distributions","C":"Neither would be taxable","D":"Both would be federally tax-exempt"},"answer":"B","explanation":"While interest income from municipal bond funds is generally federally tax-exempt, capital gains distributions are always taxable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch5-016","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which of the following would be considered \"breakpoint selling\" and a FINRA violation?","choices":{"A":"Recommending a $50,000 investment to reach a breakpoint","B":"Informing a customer about available breakpoints","C":"Recommending a $49,500 investment when $50,000 would qualify for a lower sales charge","D":"Suggesting a Letter of Intent to reach a breakpoint"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Breakpoint selling occurs when a representative recommends a purchase just below a breakpoint without informing the customer that a slightly larger purchase would qualify for a lower sales charge.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-001","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE about variable annuities?","choices":{"A":"They are invested in the insurance company's general account","B":"They guarantee a fixed rate of return","C":"They are considered securities and require FINRA registration","D":"They are regulated only by state insurance departments"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Variable annuities are invested in a separate account, offer no guaranteed returns, and are considered securities requiring registration with the SEC and FINRA regulation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-002","section":"Annuities","stem":"During the accumulation phase of a variable annuity, an investor purchases:","choices":{"A":"Annuity units","B":"Accumulation units","C":"General account units","D":"Fixed units"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During the accumulation phase, investors purchase accumulation units. Upon annuitization, these are converted to a fixed number of annuity units.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-003","section":"Annuities","stem":"A variable annuity has an Assumed Interest Rate (AIR) of 5%. If the separate account earns 7%, the annuitant's payment will:","choices":{"A":"Stay the same","B":"Increase","C":"Decrease","D":"Be eliminated"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the separate account performance exceeds the AIR, the annuitant's payment increases. The 7% return exceeds the 5% AIR, so payments increase.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-004","section":"Annuities","stem":"A 52-year-old withdraws $20,000 from a non-qualified variable annuity with $50,000 cost basis and $80,000 value. The withdrawal is subject to:","choices":{"A":"No tax because it is below the cost basis","B":"Ordinary income tax only","C":"Ordinary income tax plus 10% penalty on entire amount","D":"Ordinary income tax plus 10% penalty on $20,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Non-qualified annuities follow LIFO taxation: earnings come out first. The entire $20,000 is taxable, and since the investor is under 59 1/2, a 10% penalty also applies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-005","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which of the following is a permitted 1035 exchange?","choices":{"A":"Annuity to life insurance","B":"Life insurance to annuity","C":"Annuity to cash, then to another annuity","D":"Life insurance with one owner to annuity with a different owner"},"answer":"B","explanation":"IRC Section 1035 permits tax-free exchanges from life insurance to annuity, but NOT from annuity to life insurance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-006","section":"Annuities","stem":"Once a variable annuity is annuitized, which of the following is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"The number of annuity units will vary based on performance","B":"The value of each annuity unit is fixed","C":"The number of annuity units is fixed, but the value varies","D":"Both the number and value of annuity units are fixed"},"answer":"C","explanation":"After annuitization, the NUMBER of annuity units is FIXED, but the VALUE of each unit varies based on the separate account performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-007","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"Variable life insurance differs from whole life insurance primarily because:","choices":{"A":"Variable life has no death benefit","B":"Variable life cash value is invested in a separate account","C":"Variable life premiums are always lower","D":"Variable life is not considered a security"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Variable life insurance cash value is invested in a separate account chosen by the policyholder, exposing it to market risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-008","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which annuity payout option provides the HIGHEST monthly payment?","choices":{"A":"Life annuity with 10-year period certain","B":"Joint life with last survivor","C":"Life annuity (straight life)","D":"Life annuity with 20-year period certain"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Life annuity (straight life) provides the highest payment because it offers NO guarantees after the annuitant's death.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-009","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"An investor withdraws $10,000 from a VUL policy with $40,000 cost basis and $70,000 cash value. How is it taxed?","choices":{"A":"Fully taxable as ordinary income under LIFO","B":"Tax-free because it is less than the cost basis under FIFO","C":"Partially taxable based on the exclusion ratio","D":"Subject to 10% penalty regardless of age"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Life insurance withdrawals follow FIFO taxation. Since $10,000 is less than the $40,000 cost basis, it is entirely tax-free.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-010","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"What happens if the cash value in a variable life insurance policy declines significantly?","choices":{"A":"The death benefit is reduced proportionally","B":"The policy automatically terminates","C":"The guaranteed minimum death benefit remains intact","D":"The insurance company must restore the cash value"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Variable life insurance provides a guaranteed minimum death benefit regardless of the separate account performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-011","section":"Annuities","stem":"To sell variable annuities, a registered representative must hold:","choices":{"A":"Only a state insurance license","B":"Only a Series 6 or Series 7 license","C":"Both a securities license and a state insurance license","D":"Only a Series 65 license"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Because variable annuities are both securities AND insurance products, representatives must hold both licenses.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-012","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which is NOT an exception to the 10% early withdrawal penalty for annuities?","choices":{"A":"Withdrawals after age 59 1/2","B":"Death of the annuity owner","C":"First-time home purchase","D":"Permanent disability of the owner"},"answer":"C","explanation":"First-time home purchase is an exception for IRAs, but NOT for non-qualified annuities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-013","section":"Annuities","stem":"During the accumulation phase of a variable annuity, all of the following occur EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Earnings grow tax-deferred","B":"Dividends are automatically reinvested","C":"The investor purchases accumulation units","D":"The investor receives regular income payments"},"answer":"D","explanation":"During the accumulation phase, the investor does NOT receive income payments - that occurs during the payout (annuity) phase.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-014","section":"Annuities","stem":"The separate account of a variable annuity is BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"A guaranteed fixed account","B":"A pooled investment account similar to mutual funds","C":"A money market account with FDIC insurance","D":"The insurance company's general operating account"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The separate account functions like a family of mutual funds, offering various investment subaccounts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-015","section":"Annuities","stem":"An investor with a higher AIR will experience:","choices":{"A":"Higher initial payments and easier to maintain","B":"Lower initial payments and harder to maintain","C":"Higher initial payments and harder to maintain","D":"Lower initial payments and easier to maintain"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A higher AIR results in higher initial payments, but the separate account must continually exceed this higher rate to maintain payments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch6-016","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"Which death benefit option in variable life will provide the LARGEST payout if cash value has grown substantially?","choices":{"A":"Level death benefit (Option A)","B":"Increasing death benefit (Option B)","C":"Both options pay the same","D":"Neither option includes cash value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Option B (increasing death benefit) pays the face amount PLUS cash value, resulting in a larger benefit when cash value grows.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-001","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"In a limited partnership, which party has unlimited liability for partnership debts?","choices":{"A":"Limited partners","B":"General partner","C":"Both limited and general partners","D":"Neither partner"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The general partner has unlimited liability and is personally responsible for all partnership debts. Limited partners can only lose their invested capital plus their share of any recourse debt.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-002","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Income and losses from a DPP investment are classified as:","choices":{"A":"Active income/losses","B":"Portfolio income/losses","C":"Passive income/losses","D":"Ordinary income/losses"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Because limited partners do not actively participate in the business, all DPP income and losses are classified as passive. Passive losses can only offset passive income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-003","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which type of oil and gas program carries the HIGHEST risk?","choices":{"A":"Income (producing) program","B":"Developmental program","C":"Exploratory (wildcat) program","D":"Combination program"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Exploratory (wildcat) programs drill in unproven areas where no oil has been found. They carry the highest risk because the wells may come up dry. Income programs buying existing producing wells are the safest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-004","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Intangible drilling costs (IDCs) are:","choices":{"A":"Depreciated over 7 years","B":"100% deductible in the year incurred","C":"Not tax deductible","D":"Only deductible if oil is found"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Intangible drilling costs (wages, supplies, fuel, repairs) are 100% deductible in the year incurred, making them a major tax benefit of oil and gas DPPs. Tangible costs are depreciated over 7 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-005","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"What is the liquidation priority order for a limited partnership?","choices":{"A":"General partner, limited partners, secured creditors, general creditors","B":"Secured creditors, general creditors, limited partners, general partner","C":"Limited partners, general partner, secured creditors, general creditors","D":"General creditors, secured creditors, general partner, limited partners"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The liquidation order is: 1) Secured creditors, 2) General (unsecured) creditors, 3) Limited partners, 4) General partner. Partners are paid only after all creditors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-006","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which type of REIT invests primarily in mortgages and mortgage-backed securities?","choices":{"A":"Equity REIT","B":"Mortgage REIT (mREIT)","C":"Hybrid REIT","D":"Private REIT"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mortgage REITs (mREITs) invest in mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, earning income from interest payments. Equity REITs own physical properties and earn rental income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-007","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"To qualify as a REIT, how much of taxable income must be distributed to shareholders?","choices":{"A":"At least 75%","B":"At least 80%","C":"At least 90%","D":"100%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"REITs must distribute at least 90% of their taxable income to shareholders to qualify for pass-through tax treatment. This is similar to the mutual fund requirement under Subchapter M.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-009","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which of the following can pass through LOSSES to investors?","choices":{"A":"REITs","B":"Mutual funds","C":"DPPs (Limited Partnerships)","D":"Closed-end funds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"DPPs can pass through both income AND losses to investors. REITs and mutual funds can only pass through income - they cannot pass through losses to shareholders.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-010","section":"Suitability","stem":"An individual qualifies as an accredited investor if they have income exceeding:","choices":{"A":"$100,000 individually for the past 2 years","B":"$150,000 individually for the past 2 years","C":"$200,000 individually for the past 2 years","D":"$250,000 individually for the past 2 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An individual qualifies as an accredited investor with income exceeding $200,000 individually (or $300,000 with spouse) for the past two years with reasonable expectation of the same level.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-011","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"The typical fee structure for hedge funds is described as:","choices":{"A":"1 and 10 (1% management, 10% performance)","B":"2 and 20 (2% management, 20% performance)","C":"3 and 30 (3% management, 30% performance)","D":"0.5% flat fee only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Hedge funds typically charge \"2 and 20\": a 2% annual management fee on assets under management plus 20% of any profits generated (performance/incentive fee).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-012","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which is the MOST significant risk associated with DPP investments?","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Inflation risk","C":"Liquidity risk","D":"Currency risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Liquidity risk is the most significant DPP risk. There is no secondary market for limited partnership interests, making them extremely difficult to sell before the partnership terminates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-013","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"A limited partner who actively participates in partnership management may:","choices":{"A":"Receive additional tax benefits","B":"Lose their limited liability protection","C":"Become a preferred partner","D":"Receive a larger share of profits"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A limited partner who participates in management may lose their limited liability protection and become personally liable for partnership debts like a general partner. This is why LPs must remain passive.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-014","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Real estate DPPs that invest in raw land have:","choices":{"A":"The most tax write-offs due to high depreciation","B":"The fewest tax write-offs because land cannot be depreciated","C":"Moderate tax benefits from cost depletion","D":"No tax benefits at all"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Raw land DPPs have the fewest tax write-offs because land cannot be depreciated - only buildings and improvements can be depreciated. Raw land programs rely solely on appreciation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-015","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Excess intangible drilling costs and excess depletion from oil and gas DPPs are:","choices":{"A":"Fully deductible without limitation","B":"Tax preference items that may trigger AMT","C":"Not deductible at all","D":"Deductible only against passive income"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Excess IDCs and excess depletion are tax preference items that may subject the investor to Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT). Investors should consider AMT implications when investing in oil and gas programs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch7-016","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which statement about REITs is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"REITs are always privately traded","B":"REITs can pass through losses to investors","C":"REITs must have at least 100 shareholders","D":"REIT dividends are always tax-free"},"answer":"C","explanation":"REITs must have at least 100 shareholders and cannot be closely held (no more than 50% owned by 5 or fewer individuals). Most REITs are publicly traded, cannot pass through losses, and dividends are taxable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-001","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys an ABC 40 Call for $3 when ABC stock is trading at $43. What is the intrinsic value of this option?","choices":{"A":"$0","B":"$3","C":"$3 minus the premium","D":"$43 minus $40 = $3"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Call intrinsic value = Stock Price - Strike Price. With the stock at $43 and a strike of $40, the intrinsic value is $43 - $40 = $3. The option is $3 in-the-money.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["call-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-002","section":"Options","stem":"Which of the following describes a put option that is in-the-money?","choices":{"A":"Stock price is above the strike price","B":"Stock price is below the strike price","C":"Stock price equals the strike price","D":"The premium exceeds the intrinsic value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A put option is in-the-money when the stock price is below the strike price. This gives the put holder value because they can sell the stock at a higher price (strike) than the market price.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["put-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-003","section":"Options","stem":"An option has a premium of $7 and an intrinsic value of $4. What is the time value?","choices":{"A":"$3","B":"$4","C":"$7","D":"$11"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Time Value = Premium - Intrinsic Value. Time Value = $7 - $4 = $3. This $3 represents the extra amount investors are willing to pay for the possibility of further gains before expiration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-004","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys an ABC 60 Call for $4. What is the maximum potential loss?","choices":{"A":"Unlimited","B":"$6,000","C":"$400","D":"$5,600"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A long call buyer's maximum loss is limited to the premium paid. With a $4 premium x 100 shares = $400 maximum loss. This occurs if the option expires worthless.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-005","section":"Options","stem":"An investor writes an uncovered XYZ 45 Call for $3. What is the investor's maximum potential gain?","choices":{"A":"Unlimited","B":"$4,500","C":"$300","D":"$4,200"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A short call writer's maximum gain is the premium received. $3 x 100 shares = $300. The writer keeps this premium if the option expires worthless (stock stays at or below $45).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-006","section":"Options","stem":"What is the breakeven point for an investor who buys 1 DEF 70 Put @ $5?","choices":{"A":"$75","B":"$70","C":"$65","D":"$60"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Put breakeven = Strike Price - Premium. Breakeven = $70 - $5 = $65. The investor needs the stock to fall below $65 to profit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["put-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-007","section":"Options","stem":"An investor owns 100 shares of XYZ stock at $60 and buys an XYZ 60 Put for $4. What is the investor's maximum loss?","choices":{"A":"Unlimited","B":"$6,000","C":"$400","D":"$5,600"},"answer":"C","explanation":"With a protective put, maximum loss = Premium paid when the put strike equals the stock purchase price. The put guarantees the ability to sell at $60, so the only loss is the $4 x 100 = $400 premium.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["put-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-008","section":"Options","stem":"An investor owns 100 shares of ABC stock bought at $45 and writes an ABC 50 Call for $3. What is the maximum gain?","choices":{"A":"Unlimited","B":"$800","C":"$500","D":"$300"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Covered call max gain = (Strike - Stock Cost) + Premium = ($50 - $45) + $3 = $8 x 100 = $800. If the stock rises above $50, shares are called away at $50, plus the $3 premium received.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-009","section":"Options","stem":"Which of the following best describes a collar strategy?","choices":{"A":"Buying a call and a put at the same strike price","B":"Writing both a call and a put at the same strike price","C":"Owning stock, buying a put, and selling a call","D":"Selling stock short and buying a call for protection"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A collar involves owning the underlying stock, buying a protective put (downside protection), and selling a covered call (to offset the put cost). It creates a range of possible outcomes between the two strike prices.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-010","section":"Options","stem":"An investor executes a bull call spread by buying an ABC 40 Call for $5 and selling an ABC 45 Call for $2. What is the maximum gain?","choices":{"A":"$200","B":"$300","C":"$500","D":"$700"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Bull call spread max gain = (Higher Strike - Lower Strike) - Net Premium. Net premium = $5 - $2 = $3 (debit). Max gain = ($45 - $40) - $3 = $2 x 100 = $200.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-011","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a straddle with XYZ 50 Call @ $4 and XYZ 50 Put @ $3. What are the breakeven points?","choices":{"A":"$50 and $57","B":"$43 and $54","C":"$43 and $57","D":"$46 and $54"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Long straddle breakevens: Upper = Strike + Total Premium = $50 + $7 = $57. Lower = Strike - Total Premium = $50 - $7 = $43. The stock must move beyond these points for profit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","put-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-012","section":"Options","stem":"Which strategy profits most from a stock remaining stable (low volatility)?","choices":{"A":"Long straddle","B":"Long strangle","C":"Short straddle","D":"Bull call spread"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A short straddle writer profits when the stock stays near the strike price, allowing both options to expire worthless. The writer keeps the full premium received. High volatility is the enemy of short straddle positions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-013","section":"Options","stem":"When an S&P 500 index call option is exercised, the holder receives:","choices":{"A":"Shares representing the index","B":"Cash equal to the intrinsic value","C":"An ETF tracking the index","D":"A futures contract on the index"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Index options are cash-settled. Upon exercise, the holder receives cash equal to the intrinsic value (difference between index level and strike price x $100 multiplier). No securities are delivered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-014","section":"Options","stem":"What is the maximum expiration period for LEAPS options?","choices":{"A":"6 months","B":"1 year","C":"2 years","D":"3 years"},"answer":"D","explanation":"LEAPS (Long-Term Equity Anticipation Securities) can have expiration dates up to 3 years from the date of issuance, making them suitable for long-term strategies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-015","section":"Options","stem":"European-style options can be exercised:","choices":{"A":"Any time before expiration","B":"Only on the expiration date","C":"Only on European exchanges","D":"Only during European trading hours"},"answer":"B","explanation":"European-style options can only be exercised on the expiration date, not before. This is in contrast to American-style options, which can be exercised at any time before expiration. Most index options are European-style.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-016","section":"Options","stem":"The Options Disclosure Document (ODD) must be provided to a customer:","choices":{"A":"Within 15 days of account approval","B":"At or before account approval","C":"Before the first trade is executed","D":"Within 3 business days of the first trade"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The ODD must be provided at or before account approval. This ensures the customer understands options risks before the account is opened and any trading can begin.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-017","section":"Options","stem":"If a customer fails to return the signed Options Agreement within the required time frame, the broker-dealer must:","choices":{"A":"Close all existing positions immediately","B":"Allow only closing transactions, no new positions","C":"Continue normal trading for 30 additional days","D":"Report the customer to FINRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"If the Options Agreement is not returned within 15 days of account approval, no new positions may be opened. However, the customer may still close existing positions or exercise existing options.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-018","section":"Options","stem":"Which organization guarantees the performance of all listed options contracts?","choices":{"A":"FINRA","B":"SEC","C":"Options Clearing Corporation (OCC)","D":"CBOE"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Options Clearing Corporation (OCC) is the central clearinghouse that issues, guarantees, and clears all standardized options contracts. This guarantee eliminates counterparty risk between options traders.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch8-019","section":"Options","stem":"Which of the following options strategies requires the highest approval level?","choices":{"A":"Covered call writing","B":"Long put purchases","C":"Credit spreads","D":"Uncovered call writing"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Uncovered (naked) call writing requires the highest approval level (Level 5) because it carries unlimited risk. The stock could rise indefinitely, and the writer must deliver shares at any market price.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In a Joint Tenants with Rights of Survivorship (JTWROS) account, one of the two owners dies. What happens to the deceased owner's share of the account?","choices":{"A":"It goes to the deceased's estate through probate","B":"It is automatically transferred to the surviving owner","C":"It is split equally between the estate and the survivor","D":"The account is frozen until a court order is obtained"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In JTWROS accounts, the right of survivorship means the surviving owner automatically inherits the deceased's share. The assets bypass probate entirely and transfer directly to the survivor. This is different from Tenants in Common, where the deceased's share goes to their estate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-002","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer wants to open a brokerage account for her 10-year-old daughter. Which of the following is TRUE about this type of account?","choices":{"A":"The account can be opened as a margin account","B":"The parent and daughter can both be named as custodians","C":"Gifts to the account are irrevocable","D":"The account must use the parent's Social Security number"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under UGMA/UTMA rules, gifts to custodial accounts are irrevocable - once deposited, the money belongs to the minor and cannot be reclaimed by the donor. The account must have only one custodian and one minor, uses the minor's SSN, and cannot be a margin account.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-003","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which document is required to open a corporate brokerage account?","choices":{"A":"Partnership agreement","B":"Trust document","C":"Corporate resolution","D":"Letters testamentary"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A corporate resolution is required to open a corporate account. This document, approved by the board of directors, authorizes the corporation to open the account and specifies who can transact on its behalf. Partnership agreements are for partnerships, trust documents for trusts, and letters testamentary for estate accounts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Two business partners want to open a joint account where each can have a different ownership percentage, and if one dies, their share goes to their estate rather than the other partner. Which account type should they choose?","choices":{"A":"Joint Tenants with Rights of Survivorship (JTWROS)","B":"Tenants in Common (TIC)","C":"Partnership account","D":"Custodial account"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Tenants in Common (TIC) accounts allow for unequal ownership percentages and do not have survivorship rights - each owner's share goes to their estate upon death. JTWROS requires equal ownership and automatic survivorship. A partnership account is a separate structure for the business itself.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer with a cash account purchases $8,000 of stock on Monday. On Tuesday, before settlement, the customer sells the stock for $8,500 without having deposited any funds. What violation has occurred?","choices":{"A":"Good faith violation","B":"Freeriding violation","C":"Liquidation violation","D":"Margin violation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"This is a freeriding violation because the customer bought and sold securities without ever depositing funds to pay for the purchase. The customer profited from shares they never paid for. Freeriding results in an automatic 90-day account freeze under Regulation T.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-006","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"What is the settlement period for standard equity trades under current rules?","choices":{"A":"Same day (T+0)","B":"Trade date plus one business day (T+1)","C":"Trade date plus two business days (T+2)","D":"Trade date plus three business days (T+3)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The standard settlement period for equity securities is T+1 (trade date plus one business day), which became effective in May 2024. For example, a trade executed on Monday settles on Tuesday. This shortened settlement reduces counterparty risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["settlement"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-007","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A customer commits a freeriding violation in their cash account. What is the mandatory consequence under Regulation T?","choices":{"A":"A warning letter for the first offense","B":"A 30-day account freeze","C":"A 90-day account freeze requiring settled cash upfront","D":"Permanent account closure"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Freeriding is a federal violation under Regulation T that results in a mandatory 90-day account freeze after even a single violation. During this period, the customer can only trade if they have fully settled cash in the account before placing orders. Unlike good faith violations, there are no warnings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-008","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following securities is EXEMPT from Regulation T payment requirements?","choices":{"A":"Common stock","B":"Corporate bonds","C":"Municipal bonds","D":"Mutual funds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Municipal bonds (along with U.S. Government securities) are exempt from Regulation T payment requirements. These exempt securities are considered lower risk and highly liquid. Common stock, corporate bonds, and mutual funds are all subject to standard Reg T requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer wants to purchase $8,000 of marginable stock in their margin account. What is the minimum deposit required under Regulation T?","choices":{"A":"$2,000","B":"$4,000","C":"$6,000","D":"$8,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Regulation T requires a 50% initial margin, so 50% of $8,000 = $4,000. Since this exceeds the $2,000 FINRA minimum, the customer must deposit $4,000. The remaining $4,000 can be borrowed from the broker.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer purchases $3,000 of stock on margin. How much must they deposit?","choices":{"A":"$1,500","B":"$2,000","C":"$2,500","D":"$3,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"While 50% of $3,000 is only $1,500, the customer must deposit the greater of 50% OR the $2,000 FINRA minimum. Therefore, the required deposit is $2,000. The customer can borrow $1,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the FINRA minimum maintenance requirement for long positions in a margin account?","choices":{"A":"20% of market value","B":"25% of market value","C":"30% of market value","D":"50% of market value"},"answer":"B","explanation":"FINRA requires minimum maintenance of 25% equity for long margin positions. If equity falls below this level, the customer receives a maintenance margin call. For short positions, the minimum is 30%. Firms may set higher \"house requirements.\"","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following securities is NOT eligible for margin purchase?","choices":{"A":"NYSE-listed common stock trading at $50","B":"A mutual fund held for 60 days","C":"An IPO stock on its first day of trading","D":"An S&P 500 ETF"},"answer":"C","explanation":"New issues (IPOs) are not marginable for the first 30 days after issuance. This \"seasoning\" period allows the stock to establish a trading pattern. The NYSE stock, seasoned mutual fund, and ETF are all eligible for margin.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-013","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The agreement that allows a broker-dealer to pledge a customer's securities as collateral for margin loans is called:","choices":{"A":"Loan consent agreement","B":"Margin agreement","C":"Hypothecation agreement","D":"Power of attorney"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The hypothecation agreement allows the broker to pledge (hypothecate) the customer's securities as collateral for margin loans. The broker can rehypothecate up to 140% of the customer's debit balance. Loan consent (optional) allows lending of fully paid securities; the margin agreement authorizes borrowing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-014","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer has a long margin account with a market value of $40,000 and a debit balance of $15,000. What is the customer's equity?","choices":{"A":"$15,000","B":"$20,000","C":"$25,000","D":"$40,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Long margin equity = Long Market Value - Debit Balance. Equity = $40,000 - $15,000 = $25,000. The equity represents the customer's ownership stake after subtracting what is owed to the broker.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-015","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer has a long margin account with a $20,000 debit balance. At what market value would a 25% maintenance call be triggered?","choices":{"A":"$20,000","B":"$25,000","C":"$26,667","D":"$40,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The trigger price formula for long accounts is: DR / (1 - Maintenance %) = $20,000 / 0.75 = $26,667. If the market value falls below $26,667, equity would be below 25% and a maintenance call would be issued.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-016","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer's long margin account shows: LMV = $50,000, DR = $20,000. What is the customer's SMA?","choices":{"A":"$0","B":"$5,000","C":"$10,000","D":"$30,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"SMA = Equity - (50% x LMV). First, calculate equity: $50,000 - $20,000 = $30,000. Then: SMA = $30,000 - (50% x $50,000) = $30,000 - $25,000 = $5,000. This $5,000 represents excess equity above Reg T requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-017","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer has $8,000 in SMA. What is their buying power for purchasing additional marginable securities?","choices":{"A":"$4,000","B":"$8,000","C":"$12,000","D":"$16,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Buying Power = SMA x 2. Since Reg T requires 50% margin, each dollar of SMA supports $2 in purchases. Therefore: $8,000 x 2 = $16,000 in buying power. The customer could purchase $16,000 of securities using $8,000 of SMA as the margin deposit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-018","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer shorts 200 shares at $50, depositing 50% margin. The credit balance is:","choices":{"A":"$5,000","B":"$10,000","C":"$15,000","D":"$20,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a short sale, Credit Balance = Sale Proceeds + Margin Deposit. Sale proceeds = 200 x $50 = $10,000. Margin deposit = 50% x $10,000 = $5,000. Credit balance = $10,000 + $5,000 = $15,000. The credit balance represents the total funds held by the broker.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-019","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer tells their registered representative, \"Buy 500 shares of Microsoft when you think the price is right.\" Is this a discretionary order?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the rep chooses the timing","B":"Yes, because the rep chooses the price","C":"No, because the customer specified the security and quantity","D":"No, because verbal discretion is not allowed"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This is NOT discretionary. Time and price authority alone does not constitute discretion. Since the customer specified both the security (Microsoft) and the quantity (500 shares), the rep only has flexibility on timing and price execution, which requires no written authorization.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-020","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the Prudent Investor Rule, a fiduciary managing a trust must:","choices":{"A":"Only invest in government securities","B":"Avoid all risk regardless of the trust's objectives","C":"Consider the portfolio as a whole when evaluating investments","D":"Never delegate investment decisions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Prudent Investor Rule requires fiduciaries to evaluate investments in the context of the entire portfolio, not in isolation. This modern approach recognizes portfolio theory - a risky individual investment may be appropriate if it improves overall portfolio risk-return characteristics.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-021","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which type of power of attorney continues to be valid if the account owner becomes mentally incapacitated?","choices":{"A":"Limited power of attorney","B":"Full power of attorney","C":"Durable power of attorney","D":"Non-durable power of attorney"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A durable power of attorney specifically remains in effect even if the principal becomes incapacitated. Non-durable POAs terminate upon incapacity. \"Limited\" and \"full\" refer to the scope of authority, not durability. Durable POAs are important for estate planning.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-022","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"A customer grants their registered representative discretionary authority over their account. Which activity must be supervised?","choices":{"A":"Only trades over $10,000","B":"Only margin trades","C":"Only options trades","D":"All discretionary trades must be reviewed by a principal"},"answer":"D","explanation":"All discretionary trades require principal review. When a rep has discretion, each trade must be marked as discretionary and is subject to heightened supervision. This oversight helps prevent abuse of the authority granted by the customer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch9-023","section":"Suitability","stem":"A broker-dealer is dealing with an institutional customer that manages $75 million in assets. Regarding suitability obligations, the firm:","choices":{"A":"Has no suitability obligations to institutional customers","B":"Must apply the same suitability rules as retail customers","C":"May fulfill suitability obligations differently if the institution can independently evaluate risks","D":"Must always make the final investment decisions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For institutional customers capable of independent evaluation, suitability obligations may be fulfilled differently. The firm must still have a reasonable basis for recommendations, but can rely on the institution's ability to evaluate risks if the institution affirmatively indicates it is exercising independent judgment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is a requirement for a retirement plan to be considered \"qualified\" under IRS rules?","choices":{"A":"The plan must discriminate in favor of highly compensated employees","B":"The plan must be in writing and for the exclusive benefit of employees","C":"The plan must be funded entirely by employee contributions","D":"The plan must provide immediate 100% vesting"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A qualified plan must be established in writing and for the exclusive benefit of employees. Additionally, it must not discriminate in favor of highly compensated employees. Employer contributions are typical, and vesting can follow cliff or graded schedules - immediate vesting is not required.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-002","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under ERISA's graded vesting schedule, an employee with 4 years of service is what percentage vested in employer contributions?","choices":{"A":"40%","B":"60%","C":"80%","D":"100%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under graded vesting, employees vest at 20% per year starting in year 2. At 4 years: 20% + 20% + 20% = 60% vested. Full vesting (100%) is achieved at 6 years of service. Employee contributions are always 100% vested immediately.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-003","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation (PBGC) insures which type of retirement plan?","choices":{"A":"401(k) plans","B":"Defined benefit pension plans","C":"Individual Retirement Accounts (IRAs)","D":"403(b) plans"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The PBGC only insures defined benefit (pension) plans, which promise a specific retirement benefit. Defined contribution plans like 401(k)s, 403(b)s, and IRAs are not PBGC-insured because they are individual accounts without a promised benefit amount.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A plan fiduciary under ERISA must do all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Act solely in the interest of plan participants","B":"Diversify plan investments to minimize risk","C":"Guarantee a minimum rate of return","D":"Act with the care and skill of a prudent person"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ERISA fiduciaries must act prudently, loyally, and diversify investments, but they do NOT guarantee returns. Fiduciaries must use proper process and care in making investment decisions, but outcomes are not guaranteed. Guaranteeing returns would be impossible and is not required.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In a defined benefit pension plan, who bears the investment risk?","choices":{"A":"The employee","B":"The employer","C":"The PBGC","D":"Both employer and employee equally"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a defined benefit plan, the employer bears all investment risk because the plan promises a specific benefit regardless of investment performance. The employer must contribute enough to fund the promised benefits, whether investments perform well or poorly.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum employee deferral contribution to a 401(k) plan for 2025 for an employee under age 50?","choices":{"A":"$19,500","B":"$22,500","C":"$23,500","D":"$30,500"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For 2025, the maximum employee deferral to a 401(k) is $23,500. Employees age 50 and older can make additional catch-up contributions of $7,500 (or $11,250 if aged 60-63), bringing their maximum to $31,000 or $34,750 respectively.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-007","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A teacher at a public high school wants to contribute to an employer-sponsored retirement plan. Which plan type would be available?","choices":{"A":"401(k)","B":"403(b)","C":"SEP IRA","D":"SIMPLE IRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"403(b) plans are specifically designed for employees of public schools, 501(c)(3) tax-exempt organizations, and religious organizations. Public school teachers typically have access to 403(b) plans, not 401(k) plans, which are for private-sector employers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which retirement plan does NOT impose a 10% early withdrawal penalty for distributions before age 59 1/2?","choices":{"A":"401(k)","B":"403(b)","C":"457","D":"Traditional IRA"},"answer":"C","explanation":"457 plans (governmental deferred compensation) do not impose the 10% early withdrawal penalty for distributions before age 59 1/2. This makes them unique among tax-advantaged retirement plans. However, distributions are still subject to ordinary income tax.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An employee participates in both a 403(b) plan and a 457 plan through their employer. For 2025, what is the maximum total they can defer across both plans (assuming they are under age 50)?","choices":{"A":"$23,500","B":"$31,000","C":"$47,000","D":"$70,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"457 plan limits are separate from 401(k)/403(b) limits. An employee can contribute the full $23,500 to their 403(b) AND the full $23,500 to their 457, for a total of $47,000 in tax-advantaged deferrals. This is a significant advantage for eligible government and nonprofit employees.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum IRA contribution for 2025 for an individual age 52?","choices":{"A":"$6,500","B":"$7,000","C":"$7,500","D":"$8,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"For 2025, the base IRA contribution limit is $7,000. Individuals age 50 and older can make an additional $1,000 catch-up contribution, for a total of $8,000. This limit applies to the combined total of all Traditional and Roth IRA contributions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 45-year-old investor takes a $20,000 distribution from their Traditional IRA to pay off credit card debt. What are the tax consequences?","choices":{"A":"No tax consequences","B":"$20,000 taxed as ordinary income only","C":"$20,000 taxed as ordinary income plus 10% penalty","D":"$20,000 taxed as capital gains plus 10% penalty"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Traditional IRA distributions before age 59 1/2 are subject to ordinary income tax plus a 10% early withdrawal penalty. Paying off credit card debt does not qualify for any penalty exception. The investor owes tax on $20,000 plus a $2,000 penalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE about Roth IRAs?","choices":{"A":"Contributions are tax-deductible","B":"There are no income limits for contributions","C":"Required minimum distributions must begin at age 73","D":"Qualified distributions are tax-free"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Roth IRA qualified distributions are completely tax-free. Contributions are made with after-tax dollars (not deductible), there ARE income limits for contributions (phasing out around $150,000-$165,000 for single filers in 2025), and there are NO RMDs during the owner's lifetime.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-013","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investor receives a $50,000 distribution from their employer's 401(k) and wants to roll it into an IRA. If they take possession of the funds, the employer must withhold:","choices":{"A":"10% for federal taxes","B":"20% for federal taxes","C":"25% for federal taxes","D":"Nothing if they sign a waiver"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Distributions from employer plans that are not direct trustee-to-trustee transfers are subject to 20% mandatory federal tax withholding. To complete the rollover tax-free, the investor must deposit the full $50,000 within 60 days, making up the $10,000 withheld from other sources.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-014","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"At what age must an individual begin taking required minimum distributions (RMDs) from a Traditional IRA?","choices":{"A":"59 1/2","B":"70 1/2","C":"72","D":"73"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Under current rules, RMDs from Traditional IRAs must begin by April 1 following the year the owner turns 73. The age was increased from 72 to 73 by the SECURE 2.0 Act. Note: The RMD age is scheduled to increase to 75 in 2033.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-015","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum annual contribution to a Coverdell Education Savings Account?","choices":{"A":"$2,000 per beneficiary","B":"$7,000 per beneficiary","C":"$19,000 per beneficiary","D":"No federal limit"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Coverdell ESAs have a maximum annual contribution limit of $2,000 per beneficiary. This is much lower than 529 plans, which have no federal contribution limit. Additionally, Coverdell contributions are subject to income limits, while 529 contributions are not.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-016","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A married couple wants to \"superfund\" a 529 plan for their grandchild. What is the maximum they can contribute at once using the 5-year gift tax averaging election in 2025?","choices":{"A":"$19,000","B":"$38,000","C":"$95,000","D":"$190,000"},"answer":"D","explanation":"529 plans allow \"superfunding\" where contributors can make up to 5 years of gift tax exclusion contributions at once. For 2025, the annual exclusion is $19,000 per person. A married couple can contribute $19,000 x 2 x 5 = $190,000 without gift tax consequences.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-017","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is a qualified expense for BOTH 529 plans AND Coverdell ESAs?","choices":{"A":"K-12 school uniforms","B":"Private tutoring for elementary school","C":"College room and board","D":"Transportation to school"},"answer":"C","explanation":"College room and board is a qualified expense for both 529 plans and Coverdell ESAs. K-12 tutoring and uniforms are only covered by Coverdell, not 529. 529 plans cover K-12 tuition only (up to $10,000/year), while Coverdell covers broader K-12 expenses.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-018","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A parent withdraws $15,000 from a 529 plan. $10,000 represents contributions and $5,000 represents earnings. The funds are used to buy a car. What is taxable?","choices":{"A":"Nothing - 529 withdrawals are always tax-free","B":"$5,000 (earnings) plus 10% penalty on earnings","C":"$15,000 (entire withdrawal) plus 10% penalty","D":"$10,000 (contributions) plus 10% penalty"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For non-qualified withdrawals from 529 plans, only the earnings portion ($5,000) is taxed as ordinary income and subject to the 10% penalty. Contributions ($10,000) are never taxed or penalized since they were made with after-tax dollars. Penalty = $500; Tax on $5,000 varies by bracket.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-019","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which education savings option has income limits that prevent high-earning families from contributing?","choices":{"A":"529 Savings Plan","B":"Coverdell ESA","C":"Both have income limits","D":"Neither has income limits"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Coverdell ESAs have income limits: contributors cannot contribute if their MAGI exceeds $110,000 (single) or $220,000 (married filing jointly). 529 plans have NO income limits - anyone can contribute regardless of their income level.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-020","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 45-year-old takes a $30,000 distribution from her 401(k) to pay for her daughter's college tuition. What are the tax consequences?","choices":{"A":"Tax-free distribution for education","B":"Ordinary income tax only - education is an exception","C":"Ordinary income tax plus 10% penalty","D":"10% penalty only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The education expense exception to the 10% penalty applies only to IRAs, not employer plans like 401(k)s. The $30,000 is subject to ordinary income tax AND the 10% early withdrawal penalty ($3,000). If she had used IRA funds, she could have avoided the penalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-021","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An individual turns 73 in 2025. By what date must they take their first Required Minimum Distribution?","choices":{"A":"December 31, 2025","B":"April 1, 2026","C":"December 31, 2026","D":"April 15, 2026"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The first RMD must be taken by April 1 of the year AFTER turning 73. Since the individual turns 73 in 2025, their first RMD deadline is April 1, 2026. However, they would also need to take their 2026 RMD by December 31, 2026, resulting in two RMDs in one year if they delay.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-022","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the penalty for failing to take the full required minimum distribution from a Traditional IRA?","choices":{"A":"10% of the shortfall","B":"25% of the shortfall","C":"50% of the shortfall","D":"100% of the shortfall"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The penalty for failing to take the required RMD is 25% of the shortfall amount (reduced from the previous 50%). This penalty can be reduced to 10% if the shortfall is corrected within 2 years. This significant penalty emphasizes the importance of taking RMDs on time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-023","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 58-year-old employee leaves their company and wants to access their 401(k) without penalty. Under which circumstance could they avoid the 10% early withdrawal penalty?","choices":{"A":"They need the money for a home purchase","B":"They left the company in the year they turned 55 or later","C":"They plan to use the money for college expenses","D":"They have been unemployed for 12 weeks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The \"Rule of 55\" allows penalty-free withdrawals from an employer plan if you separate from service in or after the year you turn 55. Since this person is 58 and leaving their employer, they qualify. Note: This rule applies only to employer plans, not IRAs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch10-024","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 72-year-old wants to donate $50,000 from her Traditional IRA directly to charity. Which statement is TRUE about this Qualified Charitable Distribution (QCD)?","choices":{"A":"The distribution is included in her taxable income","B":"The distribution is excluded from income and can count toward her RMD","C":"She cannot make QCDs until age 73","D":"She can also take a charitable deduction for the $50,000"},"answer":"B","explanation":"QCDs are available starting at age 70 1/2. The distribution is excluded from taxable income (not included), can satisfy RMD requirements, and cannot also be claimed as a charitable deduction. QCDs are limited to $108,000 per year (2025).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-001","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"During the cooling-off period, which of the following is permitted?","choices":{"A":"Accepting customer orders","B":"Distributing the final prospectus","C":"Making oral offers and taking indications of interest","D":"Receiving customer payments"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During the cooling-off period, oral offers and indications of interest (non-binding) are permitted. The preliminary prospectus (red herring) can be distributed. However, no sales, orders, or payments can be accepted until the registration becomes effective.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market","securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-002","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"In a firm commitment underwriting, who bears the risk of unsold securities?","choices":{"A":"The issuer","B":"The underwriting syndicate","C":"The selling group","D":"The SEC"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a firm commitment underwriting, the syndicate purchases all securities from the issuer and assumes the risk of any unsold shares. The underwriters act as principals (dealers), not agents. If they cannot sell all shares to the public, they must hold or sell them at a loss.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-003","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following securities is exempt from registration under the Securities Act of 1933?","choices":{"A":"Common stock of a Fortune 500 company","B":"Corporate bonds of an industrial company","C":"Municipal general obligation bonds","D":"IPO shares of a technology startup"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Municipal bonds are exempt from registration under the Securities Act of 1933. Other exempt securities include U.S. Government securities, bank securities, and non-profit organization securities. Corporate stocks and bonds must be registered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933","municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-004","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"The portion of the underwriter's spread that is paid to the dealer who actually sells the securities to investors is called the:","choices":{"A":"Manager's fee","B":"Underwriting fee","C":"Selling concession","D":"Reallowance"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The selling concession is the portion of the spread paid to the firm that actually sells the securities to investors. The manager's fee goes to the lead underwriter, the underwriting fee compensates syndicate members for underwriting risk, and the reallowance goes to non-syndicate dealers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-005","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"The New York Stock Exchange is classified as what type of market?","choices":{"A":"Negotiated market","B":"Auction market","C":"Dealer market","D":"Over-the-counter market"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The NYSE operates as an auction market where buyers and sellers meet in a centralized location and orders compete against each other. In contrast, NASDAQ is a negotiated/dealer market where multiple market makers compete to execute trades.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-006","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A stock is quoted at 45.50 - 45.75. An investor wanting to purchase 100 shares would pay:","choices":{"A":"$4,550","B":"$4,562.50","C":"$4,575","D":"$4,525"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Investors buy at the ask (offer) price. The ask price is $45.75, so 100 shares would cost $45.75 x 100 = $4,575. The bid price of $45.50 is what the investor would receive if selling.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["secondary-market","market-makers"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-007","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"Which entity maintains fair and orderly markets for assigned securities on the NYSE?","choices":{"A":"Market Maker","B":"Designated Market Maker (DMM)","C":"Floor Broker","D":"Specialist Clerk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Designated Market Maker (DMM), formerly known as the Specialist, is responsible for maintaining fair and orderly markets for their assigned securities on the NYSE. They provide liquidity, execute orders, and facilitate price discovery.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["market-makers","secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-008","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"Trading of NYSE-listed securities in the over-the-counter market is known as:","choices":{"A":"First market trading","B":"Second market trading","C":"Third market trading","D":"Fourth market trading"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Third market trading refers to exchange-listed securities trading in the OTC market. First market is exchange trading, second market is OTC trading of OTC securities, and fourth market is direct institution-to-institution trading without intermediaries.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-009","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A stock is trading at $40. Which of the following orders would be entered BELOW the current market price?","choices":{"A":"Buy stop and sell limit","B":"Buy limit and sell stop","C":"Buy limit and sell limit","D":"Buy stop and sell stop"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Remember BLiSS: Buy Limit and Sell Stop are placed below the market. Buy limits seek a lower purchase price; sell stops protect long positions by triggering if price falls. SLoBS (Sell Limit, Buy Stop) are placed above the market.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-010","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"An investor owns 500 shares of XYZ at $60 and wants to protect against a significant price decline. Which order should they place?","choices":{"A":"Buy stop at $55","B":"Sell stop at $55","C":"Buy limit at $55","D":"Sell limit at $55"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A sell stop order protects a long position. Placed below the market at $55, it will trigger if the price falls to $55, converting to a market order to sell and limiting the investor's loss. Buy stops protect short positions; limit orders are for price targets, not loss protection.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-011","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"What happens when a sell stop order is triggered?","choices":{"A":"It becomes a limit order at the stop price","B":"It becomes a market order","C":"It is cancelled","D":"It remains a stop order until filled"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a stop order is triggered (price reaches the stop price), it becomes a market order and executes at the next available price. This means the execution price may be above or below the stop price, especially in fast-moving markets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-012","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"An order designated as \"GTC\" will:","choices":{"A":"Expire at the end of the trading day","B":"Execute immediately in full or be cancelled","C":"Remain open until executed or cancelled by the investor","D":"Execute at the closing price"},"answer":"C","explanation":"GTC (Good-Til-Canceled) orders remain open until they are either executed or cancelled by the customer. Day orders expire at the end of the trading day. Fill-or-Kill (FOK) must execute immediately in full or be cancelled.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-013","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A customer places a buy limit order at $35 on a stock trading at $37. The stock goes ex-dividend for $0.50. What happens to the order?","choices":{"A":"The order remains at $35","B":"The order is reduced to $34.50","C":"The order is cancelled","D":"The order is increased to $35.50"},"answer":"B","explanation":"By default, buy limit and sell stop orders (BLiSS orders below the market) are reduced by the dividend amount on the ex-dividend date. The order adjusts from $35 to $34.50 ($35 - $0.50). The customer can add \"DNR\" (Do Not Reduce) to prevent this adjustment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-014","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"What is the regular way settlement period for corporate stock trades?","choices":{"A":"Same day (T+0)","B":"Trade date plus one business day (T+1)","C":"Trade date plus two business days (T+2)","D":"Trade date plus three business days (T+3)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Regular way settlement for corporate stocks is T+1 (trade date plus one business day). This standard became effective May 28, 2024. For example, a trade executed on Monday settles on Tuesday.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-015","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"TRACE is used to report transactions in which type of security?","choices":{"A":"Municipal bonds","B":"Corporate bonds","C":"U.S. Treasury securities","D":"Listed equity securities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"TRACE (Trade Reporting and Compliance Engine) is FINRA's system for reporting corporate bond transactions. Municipal bonds are reported through EMMA (MSRB). Treasury securities have their own reporting, and equities are reported through the Consolidated Tape.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds","finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-016","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"The record date for a cash dividend is Thursday. What is the ex-dividend date?","choices":{"A":"Tuesday","B":"Wednesday","C":"Thursday","D":"Friday"},"answer":"B","explanation":"With T+1 settlement, the ex-dividend date is one business day before the record date. If record date is Thursday, ex-date is Wednesday. Buyers on Tuesday (before ex-date) settle Wednesday and are on record; buyers Wednesday or later settle too late.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-017","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"Which organization holds securities in electronic book-entry form and facilitates transfers between broker-dealers?","choices":{"A":"NSCC","B":"DTC","C":"FINRA","D":"SEC"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Depository Trust Company (DTC) holds securities in electronic book-entry form, eliminating the need for physical certificates. NSCC (National Securities Clearing Corporation) handles clearing and netting. Both are subsidiaries of DTCC.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-018","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A broker-dealer executes a trade from its own inventory for a customer. In this transaction, the firm is acting as:","choices":{"A":"Agent","B":"Principal","C":"Broker","D":"Custodian"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a firm trades from its own inventory (buys from or sells to a customer), it acts as a principal (dealer). The compensation is a markup (selling) or markdown (buying). When acting as agent (broker), the firm facilitates trades between parties and earns a commission.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["market-makers"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-019","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which organization is responsible for administering securities qualification exams such as the Series 7?","choices":{"A":"SEC","B":"FINRA","C":"MSRB","D":"DTCC"},"answer":"B","explanation":"FINRA (Financial Industry Regulatory Authority) administers qualification examinations including the Series 7. FINRA is a self-regulatory organization that oversees broker-dealers. The SEC supervises FINRA but does not directly administer exams.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-020","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A market maker is required to do all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Continuously post bid and ask quotes","B":"Honor quotes up to the stated size","C":"Guarantee a profit for investors","D":"Maintain a two-sided market"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Market makers must continuously quote bid and ask prices, honor those quotes up to stated sizes, and maintain two-sided markets (willing to buy and sell). They are NOT required to guarantee profits - investors can still lose money.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["market-makers"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-021","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"Which entity maintains shareholder records and processes ownership transfers for securities?","choices":{"A":"Custodian","B":"Transfer agent","C":"Clearing corporation","D":"Market maker"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Transfer agents maintain official records of security ownership, process transfers between buyers and sellers, issue and cancel certificates, and distribute dividends. Custodians hold securities for safekeeping but don't maintain the official ownership records.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-series7-ch11-022","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The MSRB creates rules for municipal securities dealers but does NOT:","choices":{"A":"Create continuing education requirements","B":"Operate the EMMA system","C":"Enforce its own rules","D":"Regulate municipal advisors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The MSRB (Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board) creates rules but does NOT have enforcement authority. Enforcement of MSRB rules is handled by FINRA (for broker-dealers) and the SEC. The MSRB does operate EMMA and regulates both dealers and municipal advisors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-001","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which regulatory body creates rules for the municipal securities market but does NOT have enforcement authority?","choices":{"A":"SEC","B":"FINRA","C":"MSRB","D":"Federal Reserve"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The MSRB (Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board) creates rules for municipal securities dealers and municipal advisors but lacks enforcement authority. FINRA and the SEC enforce MSRB rules. The MSRB also operates the EMMA system for municipal market transparency.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["msrb"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-002","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which of the following sanctions can FINRA impose on a registered representative who violates industry rules?","choices":{"A":"Criminal prosecution","B":"Imprisonment","C":"Permanent bar from the securities industry","D":"Asset seizure"},"answer":"C","explanation":"FINRA can bar individuals permanently from the securities industry, as well as impose fines, suspensions, and censures. Criminal prosecution, imprisonment, and asset seizure are powers of government agencies (DOJ, SEC) and courts, not FINRA.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-003","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which federal agency has authority over margin requirements under Regulation T?","choices":{"A":"SEC","B":"FINRA","C":"Federal Reserve Board","D":"Treasury Department"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Federal Reserve Board has authority over margin requirements through Regulation T (broker-dealer credit), Regulation U (bank credit), and Regulation X (borrowers). The Securities Exchange Act of 1934 delegated this authority to the Fed.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["frb","margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-004","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"The SEC was created by which legislation?","choices":{"A":"Securities Act of 1933","B":"Securities Exchange Act of 1934","C":"Investment Company Act of 1940","D":"Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) was created by the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, which governs the secondary markets. The Securities Act of 1933 governs primary market offerings but predates the SEC's creation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["sec","securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-005","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which suitability obligation requires that a recommendation be suitable for at least some investors?","choices":{"A":"Customer-specific suitability","B":"Reasonable-basis suitability","C":"Quantitative suitability","D":"Institutional suitability"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Reasonable-basis suitability requires that a recommendation be suitable for at least some investors based on the product's characteristics. This requires the representative to understand the product before recommending it to anyone. Customer-specific suitability then considers the individual customer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-006","section":"Suitability","stem":"Under Regulation Best Interest, which obligation requires broker-dealers to provide Form CRS to retail customers?","choices":{"A":"Care Obligation","B":"Conflict of Interest Obligation","C":"Disclosure Obligation","D":"Compliance Obligation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Disclosure Obligation under Reg BI requires broker-dealers to provide Form CRS (Customer Relationship Summary) to retail customers. This two-page document explains the firm's services, fees, conflicts, and disciplinary history in plain English.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reg-bi","disclosure"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-007","section":"Suitability","stem":"A registered representative makes 50 trades in a customer's account over one month, each individually suitable. However, the combined effect generates excessive commissions relative to the account size. This violates which suitability obligation?","choices":{"A":"Reasonable-basis suitability","B":"Customer-specific suitability","C":"Quantitative suitability","D":"Product suitability"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Quantitative suitability addresses the total number of transactions, even if each is individually suitable. Excessive trading (churning) violates this obligation because the cumulative trading activity is not in the customer's best interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-008","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following is NOT a factor in a customer's investment profile under FINRA Rule 2111?","choices":{"A":"Risk tolerance","B":"Tax status","C":"Credit score","D":"Investment time horizon"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Credit score is not a factor in the investment profile under Rule 2111. The required factors include age, other investments, financial situation, tax status, investment objectives, experience, time horizon, liquidity needs, and risk tolerance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-009","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which statement about Regulation Best Interest and FINRA Rule 2111 is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Rule 2111 applies only to retail customers","B":"Reg BI compliance satisfies Rule 2111 requirements","C":"Both standards are identical in their requirements","D":"Reg BI applies to institutional customers only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Compliance with Reg BI satisfies Rule 2111 because the \"best interest\" standard is higher than the \"suitability\" standard. Rule 2111 applies to all customers while Reg BI applies only to retail customers. The standards are similar but Reg BI has enhanced requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["reg-bi","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative sends an email about a new bond offering to 30 retail customers. This communication is classified as:","choices":{"A":"Correspondence","B":"Retail communication","C":"Institutional communication","D":"Internal communication"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A retail communication is any written communication distributed to MORE than 25 retail investors within any 30-day period. Since this email went to 30 retail customers, it is a retail communication requiring principal pre-approval.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which category of communication requires principal approval BEFORE first use?","choices":{"A":"Correspondence only","B":"Institutional communications only","C":"Retail communications","D":"All communications equally"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Retail communications require principal approval before first use or filing with FINRA (whichever comes first). Correspondence and institutional communications do not require pre-approval, though firms must have supervisory procedures for reviewing them.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-012","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following statements would be PROHIBITED in a retail communication?","choices":{"A":"\"This investment has risks that should be carefully considered\"","B":"\"Past performance does not guarantee future results\"","C":"\"This bond is guaranteed to provide 5% annual returns\"","D":"\"Please read the prospectus before investing\""},"answer":"C","explanation":"Guarantees of investment returns are prohibited in communications with the public. All investments carry risk, and promising specific returns is misleading. Communications must be fair and balanced, presenting both risks and potential benefits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-013","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An entity qualifies as an institutional investor for communications purposes if it has assets of at least:","choices":{"A":"$10 million","B":"$25 million","C":"$50 million","D":"$100 million"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under FINRA rules, persons or entities with at least $50 million in assets qualify as institutional investors. Other institutional investors include banks, insurance companies, registered investment companies, registered investment advisers, and government entities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-014","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A new FINRA member firm must file retail communications with FINRA's Advertising Regulation Department:","choices":{"A":"Within 10 business days after first use","B":"At least 10 business days before first use","C":"Within 30 days after first use","D":"Only if requested by FINRA"},"answer":"B","explanation":"New member firms (in their first year of membership) must file retail communications at least 10 business days BEFORE first use. This allows FINRA to review materials before they reach the public. Established firms file within 10 business days after first use.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-015","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An employee of a pharmaceutical company tells their friend about a pending FDA approval before the public announcement. The friend buys stock and profits. Who can be held liable for insider trading?","choices":{"A":"Only the friend who traded","B":"Only the employee who shared the information","C":"Both the employee (tipper) and the friend (tippee)","D":"Neither - the friend is not a company insider"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Both the tipper (employee who shared the information) and the tippee (friend who traded) can be held liable for insider trading. The employee violated their duty by sharing material, non-public information, and the friend violated the law by trading on it.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-016","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A trader places large buy orders with no intention of executing them, then cancels the orders after the price moves. This practice is called:","choices":{"A":"Front-running","B":"Spoofing/Layering","C":"Churning","D":"Interpositioning"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Spoofing (or layering) involves placing orders with the intent to cancel them before execution, designed to create a false impression of supply or demand and manipulate prices. This is a form of market manipulation prohibited by securities laws.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["market-makers","order-types"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-017","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A broker learns that a large institutional customer is about to place a major buy order. Before executing the customer's order, the broker buys shares for their personal account. This is:","choices":{"A":"Acceptable trading","B":"Front-running","C":"Stabilization","D":"Arbitrage"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Front-running is trading ahead of a customer order while possessing material, non-public market information about that order. FINRA Rule 5270 prohibits this practice because it allows the broker to profit at the customer's expense.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-018","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative wants to sell limited partnership interests to clients. The partnerships are not offered through their firm. What must they do?","choices":{"A":"Proceed without notification since it's outside the firm","B":"Provide written notice to their firm and obtain approval","C":"Only inform FINRA directly","D":"Resign from the firm before making any sales"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under FINRA Rule 3280 (Private Securities Transactions), a representative must provide written notice to their employer before participating in securities transactions outside the firm. If compensation is involved, the firm must approve and supervise the activity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-019","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"Which of the following is the ONLY legal form of market manipulation?","choices":{"A":"Wash sales during an IPO","B":"Stabilization by underwriters during distribution","C":"Matched orders to create volume","D":"Marking the close on the last day of a quarter"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Stabilization is the only legal form of market manipulation. Underwriters may place bids to support the price of a new issue during distribution. Stabilizing bids cannot exceed the public offering price and must be disclosed in the prospectus.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-020","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"What is the maximum SIPC protection for securities and cash combined in a customer account?","choices":{"A":"$100,000","B":"$250,000","C":"$500,000","D":"$1,000,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"SIPC provides maximum protection of $500,000 per customer, including a $250,000 limit specifically for cash. If a customer has $400,000 in securities and $150,000 in cash, the cash would be protected to $250,000, and securities would be fully protected within the $500,000 total limit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-021","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"Which of the following is NOT protected by SIPC?","choices":{"A":"Common stock held in a brokerage account","B":"Mutual fund shares","C":"Losses due to market decline","D":"Corporate bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"SIPC protects against broker-dealer failure, NOT investment losses. If a customer's investments decline in value, SIPC does not cover those losses. SIPC protects the securities and cash that are supposed to be in the account when the firm fails.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-022","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under a firm's Customer Identification Program (CIP), which information must be obtained before opening an account?","choices":{"A":"Name, address, date of birth, and identification number","B":"Investment experience and risk tolerance only","C":"Net worth and annual income","D":"Employment history and references"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Customer Identification Program (CIP) requires firms to obtain four pieces of information before opening an account: name, address, date of birth, and identification number (usually SSN). This information is used to verify identity for anti-money laundering purposes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["customer-documentation","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-023","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A Suspicious Activity Report (SAR) must be filed for transactions involving potential illegal activity when the amount is:","choices":{"A":"$2,500 or more","B":"$5,000 or more","C":"$10,000 or more","D":"$25,000 or more"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A SAR must be filed for transactions of $5,000 or more that involve potential illegal activity, such as money laundering or fraud. CTRs (Currency Transaction Reports) are filed for cash transactions over $10,000, which is a separate reporting requirement.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-024","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under Regulation S-P, firms must provide customers with a privacy notice:","choices":{"A":"Only when the account is opened","B":"Initially and then annually","C":"Only upon customer request","D":"Every quarter"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Regulation S-P requires firms to provide an initial privacy notice when the customer relationship begins and then annually thereafter. The notice must explain what information is collected, how it is shared, and how it is protected.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec","disclosure"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-025","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under FINRA rules, what is the maximum value of gifts a registered representative can give to an employee of another firm per year?","choices":{"A":"$50","B":"$100","C":"$250","D":"$500"},"answer":"B","explanation":"FINRA Rule 3220 limits gifts to associated persons of other member firms to $100 per person per year. This limit does not apply to reasonable business entertainment where the representative is present, or to promotional items of nominal value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-026","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative wants to work part-time at a real estate agency on weekends. What must they do?","choices":{"A":"Nothing - real estate is not a securities activity","B":"Provide written notice to their firm","C":"Obtain FINRA approval directly","D":"Resign from their securities position"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under FINRA Rule 3270, representatives must provide written notice to their firm before engaging in any outside business activity, including non-securities related work like real estate. The firm will evaluate the activity for potential conflicts or concerns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-027","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The Regulatory Element of continuing education must be completed:","choices":{"A":"Annually","B":"Every two years","C":"Within 120 days of the 2nd registration anniversary, then periodically","D":"Only once after passing the Series 7"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Regulatory Element must be completed within 120 days of the second registration anniversary, then on the 5th, 8th anniversary, etc. (every 3 years after the initial requirement). Failure to complete results in inactive registration status.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-028","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"FINRA Rule 2010 requires members to observe high standards of commercial honor. This rule can be violated:","choices":{"A":"Only when another specific FINRA rule is also violated","B":"Only in cases involving customer complaints","C":"Even when no specific rule is broken, if conduct is unethical","D":"Only by registered representatives, not firms"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Rule 2010 is a broad catch-all ethics rule. It can be violated even when no specific rule is broken, as long as the conduct falls short of \"high standards of commercial honor and just and equitable principles of trade.\" It applies to both firms and individuals.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series7-series7-ch12-029","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative is convicted of a felony. What is the consequence under securities regulations?","choices":{"A":"No consequence if the felony is not securities-related","B":"A warning letter from FINRA","C":"Statutory disqualification from the industry","D":"A 6-month suspension"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A felony conviction within the past 10 years results in statutory disqualification, regardless of whether the felony was securities-related. The person cannot associate with a FINRA member firm unless the firm obtains a waiver through a membership application.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-s7-q-240","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following must be disclosed on Form U4?","choices":{"A":"A traffic violation resulting in a fine","B":"A customer complaint settled for $25,000 alleging a sales practice violation","C":"A misdemeanor for jaywalking","D":"A verbal warning from a supervisor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A customer complaint settled for $15,000 or more that alleges a sales practice violation must be disclosed on Form U4. A $25,000 settlement exceeds that threshold and is reportable. Settlements below $15,000, minor traffic violations, non-investment-related misdemeanors, and informal verbal warnings are not reportable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-s7-q-255","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"Regular way settlement on Treasury bonds is:","choices":{"A":"Same day","B":"Next business day (T+1)","C":"Second business day (T+2)","D":"Fifth business day"},"answer":"B","explanation":"U.S. Treasury securities settle T+1 (next business day) in regular way settlement. Since May 28, 2024, corporate and municipal securities also settle T+1, so Treasuries are no longer faster than other securities. Cash (same-day) settlement is a separate, non-regular-way arrangement.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["settlement","government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-s7-q-465","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"By what age must all assets in a Coverdell Education Savings Account be distributed to avoid tax penalties?","choices":{"A":"Age 18","B":"Age 21","C":"Age 30","D":"Age 59 1/2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Coverdell ESA assets must be distributed by the time the beneficiary reaches age 30. If not used for qualified education expenses by then, the remaining balance is subject to income tax plus a 10% penalty on earnings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv1","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A municipal analyst is reviewing bond offerings. Which project would MOST likely require a feasibility study as part of the official statement?","choices":{"A":"General obligation bonds for a new public school","B":"Bonds backed by property tax assessments","C":"Toll road revenue bonds for a new highway","D":"Unlimited tax bonds for city infrastructure"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Toll road revenue bonds require a feasibility study because they are revenue bonds - repayment depends entirely on the project generating sufficient toll revenue. The study analyzes projected traffic, toll rates, operating costs, and debt coverage. GO bonds (A, D) and assessment bonds (B) are backed by taxing power, not project revenues, so they do not require feasibility studies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv2","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor wants to purchase preferred stock with a current yield of at least 10%. If the preferred stock has a 7% stated dividend and $50 par value, what is the MAXIMUM price the investor should pay?","choices":{"A":"$35.00","B":"$50.00","C":"$70.00","D":"$100.00"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Current Yield = Annual Dividend / Current Market Price. Annual dividend = 7% x $50 = $3.50. To achieve 10% current yield: Price = $3.50 / 0.10 = $35.00. At $35, the investor receives $3.50 dividend / $35 price = 10% current yield. Any price above $35 would yield less than 10%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv3","section":"Options","stem":"An investor is long 1 XYZ June 80 call when XYZ declares a 25% stock dividend. After the adjustment, the investor will hold:","choices":{"A":"1 call covering 125 shares at a strike price of $64","B":"1 call covering 100 shares at a strike price of $100","C":"1.25 calls covering 100 shares each at $80","D":"1 call covering 100 shares at a strike price of $64"},"answer":"A","explanation":"For stock dividends, the OCC adjusts the contract: shares covered increase and strike price decreases proportionally. With a 25% stock dividend: New shares = 100 x 1.25 = 125 shares. New strike = $80 / 1.25 = $64. The total contract value remains the same: 100 x $80 = $8,000 = 125 x $64.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv4","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"An investor seeking income from commercial real estate mortgages without directly owning property should consider:","choices":{"A":"Equity REITs","B":"Real estate limited partnerships","C":"Mortgage REITs","D":"Raw land investments"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Mortgage REITs (mREITs) invest in mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, providing income from commercial real estate debt without property ownership. Equity REITs own properties directly. Limited partnerships often require direct property involvement. Raw land produces no income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv5","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative sends an identical email about a new investment opportunity to 30 retail clients over a two-week period. Under FINRA Rule 2210, this communication is classified as:","choices":{"A":"Correspondence requiring no prior approval","B":"Institutional communication","C":"Retail communication requiring principal approval before first use","D":"Internal communication exempt from all rules"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under FINRA Rule 2210, any written communication distributed to more than 25 retail investors within any 30-calendar-day period is classified as retail communication. Retail communications require principal approval BEFORE first use or filing with FINRA. Here, 30 clients exceeds the 25-person threshold.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv6","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A client with a high risk tolerance seeks maximum capital appreciation and is comfortable with significant volatility. Which fund type is MOST aligned with this objective?","choices":{"A":"Government bond fund","B":"Aggressive growth fund investing in turnaround situations","C":"Money market fund","D":"Balanced fund"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Aggressive growth funds (including special situation funds) invest in companies undergoing turnarounds, restructurings, or other special circumstances with high growth potential. These are suitable for investors with high risk tolerance seeking maximum capital appreciation, accepting significant volatility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv7","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 45-year-old taxpayer takes a $20,000 distribution from their traditional IRA to pay for their daughter's college tuition. The distribution will be:","choices":{"A":"Subject to 10% early withdrawal penalty plus ordinary income tax","B":"Tax-free and penalty-free","C":"Subject to ordinary income tax but exempt from the 10% penalty","D":"Subject to capital gains tax only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Qualified higher education expenses are an exception to the 10% early withdrawal penalty for IRA distributions before age 59.5. The distribution is still taxed as ordinary income, but the penalty is waived. This applies to tuition, fees, books, supplies, and room and board for enrolled students.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv8","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under SEC \"access equals delivery\" rules, a mutual fund prospectus delivery requirement can be satisfied by:","choices":{"A":"Verbal summary of key points over the phone","B":"Providing electronic access to the prospectus online with proper notice","C":"Delivering the prospectus within 90 days of purchase","D":"Sending only the Statement of Additional Information"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The SEC's \"access equals delivery\" rule allows prospectus delivery requirements to be satisfied by providing investors with notice that the prospectus is available electronically (online) and explaining how to access it. The prospectus must be publicly accessible on the fund's website or through EDGAR.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv9","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"A commercial property generates $500,000 in net operating income and has annual debt service of $400,000. The debt service coverage ratio (DSCR) is:","choices":{"A":"0.80","B":"1.00","C":"1.25","D":"1.80"},"answer":"C","explanation":"DSCR = Net Operating Income (NOI) / Annual Debt Service. DSCR = $500,000 / $400,000 = 1.25. A DSCR above 1.0 indicates the property generates enough income to cover debt payments. Lenders typically require DSCR of 1.20-1.25 or higher for commercial mortgages.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv10","section":"Options","stem":"An investor writes 2 ABC November 40 calls at $5 each and writes 2 ABC November 40 puts at $3 each. At which stock price would the investor experience a LOSS?","choices":{"A":"$35","B":"$40","C":"$45","D":"$50"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This is a short straddle. Total premium received = ($5 + $3) x 2 contracts = $16 per share ($1,600 total). Breakeven points: Upper = $40 + $8 = $48. Lower = $40 - $8 = $32. At $50, the call is $10 in-the-money, loss = $10 - $8 premium = $2 per share loss. The put expires worthless. $50 is above the upper breakeven of $48, so there is a loss.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv11","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor in the 35% federal tax bracket holds a collateralized mortgage obligation (CMO). The interest income from this security is:","choices":{"A":"Tax-exempt at federal and state levels","B":"Taxed as ordinary income at federal and state levels","C":"Taxed only at the state level","D":"Taxed at capital gains rates"},"answer":"B","explanation":"CMO interest is fully taxable as ordinary income at both federal and state levels. CMOs are backed by mortgage pools (usually government agency or private label), and unlike municipal bonds, they offer no tax advantages. The interest is taxed at the investor's marginal tax rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv12","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A U.S. corporation wants to issue securities without SEC registration. Under Regulation S, this is possible if the offering:","choices":{"A":"Is made exclusively to non-U.S. persons in offshore transactions","B":"Is limited to 35 purchasers in the United States","C":"Uses only accredited investors","D":"Is completed within 180 days"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Regulation S provides a safe harbor for offerings made outside the United States. To qualify, the offer and sale must be made in an \"offshore transaction\" to persons reasonably believed to be non-U.S. persons, with no directed selling efforts in the U.S. The securities have resale restrictions to prevent flowback into U.S. markets.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv13","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"A technical analyst observes that for 15 consecutive trading days, over 400 stocks on the NYSE have advanced while fewer than 100 have declined. This pattern suggests the market is:","choices":{"A":"Overbought and may be due for a correction","B":"Oversold and ready for a rally","C":"In a balanced state","D":"Experiencing normal volatility"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When advances consistently and significantly exceed declines over an extended period, the advance-decline ratio indicates an overbought condition. Technical analysts interpret this as the market being extended and potentially due for a pullback or correction as buying momentum becomes exhausted.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv14","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A convertible preferred stock pays a $4 annual dividend and is convertible into 2 shares of common stock. If the preferred trades at $50 and the common at $22, what is the conversion premium?","choices":{"A":"10.00%","B":"13.64%","C":"8.00%","D":"4.55%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Conversion value = 2 shares x $22 = $44. Conversion premium = (Market Price - Conversion Value) / Conversion Value. Premium = ($50 - $44) / $44 = $6 / $44 = 13.64%. The preferred trades at a 13.64% premium over its conversion value, reflecting the dividend advantage and downside protection.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv15","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, which of the following would be considered a NON-accredited investor?","choices":{"A":"An individual with $1.2 million net worth including primary residence","B":"A partnership where all partners are accredited investors","C":"A corporation with $4 million in total assets","D":"A registered investment adviser"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A corporation must have total assets exceeding $5 million to qualify as an accredited investor. This corporation with $4 million in assets does not meet the threshold. Individual net worth excludes primary residence (must be over $1M), so option A qualifies. Entities composed entirely of accredited investors qualify. Registered investment advisers are accredited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv16","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor wants fixed income with the LEAST interest rate risk. Which bond would you recommend?","choices":{"A":"30-year Treasury bond","B":"3-year corporate note","C":"15-year municipal bond","D":"20-year zero coupon bond"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Interest rate risk increases with maturity and decreases with coupon payments. The 3-year corporate note has the shortest duration among the choices, making it least sensitive to interest rate changes. Zero coupon bonds (D) have the highest duration for any given maturity because there are no interim cash flows.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv17","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A customer purchases municipal bonds on Monday, September 15th. Under current settlement rules, when must payment be made?","choices":{"A":"Tuesday, September 16th (T+1)","B":"Wednesday, September 17th (T+2)","C":"Thursday, September 18th (T+3)","D":"Monday, September 22nd (T+5)"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Municipal bonds settle on a T+1 basis (trade date plus one business day), which is the same as stocks and corporate bonds under current SEC rules effective May 2024. If traded on Monday, settlement occurs on Tuesday. Previously, munis settled T+2.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds","settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv18","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor buys a corporate bond at 108 with a 6% coupon, 10 years to maturity. If the investor does NOT elect to amortize the premium and holds to maturity, what is the tax consequence at maturity?","choices":{"A":"$80 capital loss","B":"No gain or loss","C":"$80 capital gain","D":"$60 ordinary income"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The bond was purchased at 108 ($1,080) and will mature at par ($1,000). If the investor does not amortize the premium, the $80 difference ($1,080 - $1,000) is recognized as a capital loss at maturity. Alternatively, the investor could elect to amortize the premium annually, reducing interest income over the holding period.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv19","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which employee would benefit MOST from their employer switching from a 401(k) to a defined benefit pension plan?","choices":{"A":"25-year-old earning $45,000 annually","B":"35-year-old earning $75,000 annually","C":"45-year-old earning $120,000 annually","D":"58-year-old earning $200,000 annually"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Defined benefit plans favor older, higher-paid employees because benefits are based on final average salary and years of service. The 58-year-old has the highest salary and least time to retirement, so the employer must make larger contributions to fund their benefit. Younger employees benefit more from defined contribution plans with compound growth over time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv20","section":"Options","stem":"An investor establishes a bull put spread by buying 1 XYZ June 45 put at $2 and selling 1 XYZ June 50 put at $5. What market outlook does this position reflect?","choices":{"A":"Strongly bearish - expects significant decline","B":"Moderately bullish - expects stock to stay above $50","C":"Neutral - expects no price movement","D":"Strongly bullish - expects significant increase"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A bull put spread is a credit spread (net premium received = $5 - $2 = $3). Maximum profit occurs if both puts expire worthless, which happens when the stock stays above the higher strike ($50). The investor has a moderately bullish outlook, expecting the stock to remain stable or rise. Maximum profit is $3, maximum loss is $2 (spread width minus credit).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv21","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor purchases a municipal bond in the secondary market at a discount (below par). How should the discount be treated for tax purposes?","choices":{"A":"The discount may be accreted annually as taxable income","B":"The discount is always tax-free","C":"The discount must be recognized as ordinary income at purchase","D":"The discount is treated as a capital loss"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When a municipal bond is purchased at a market discount in the secondary market, the investor may elect to accrete the discount as taxable ordinary income annually. Alternatively, the discount can be recognized at sale or maturity as ordinary income (not capital gain). Note: original issue discount (OID) on munis is tax-exempt.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv22","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A TIPS bond has a 4% coupon rate. After one year of 2.5% inflation, the adjusted principal is $1,025. What is the semi-annual interest payment?","choices":{"A":"$20.00","B":"$20.50","C":"$40.00","D":"$41.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"TIPS interest is calculated on the inflation-adjusted principal. Annual interest = $1,025 x 4% = $41. Semi-annual payment = $41 / 2 = $20.50. The coupon rate (4%) stays constant, but it is applied to the inflation-adjusted principal ($1,025), not the original par value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv23","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"In a municipal bond underwriting, the spread is $10 per bond. The manager's fee is $1.50, the additional takedown is $5.50, and the selling concession is $3.00. A syndicate member sells bonds from the account. The total takedown is:","choices":{"A":"$3.00","B":"$5.50","C":"$8.50","D":"$10.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Total takedown = Additional takedown + Selling concession = $5.50 + $3.00 = $8.50. The total takedown is what a syndicate member earns for selling bonds. The manager's fee ($1.50) is separate compensation for managing the syndicate. The full spread ($10) = Manager's fee + Total takedown.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["municipal-bonds","primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv24","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under Regulation D, which of the following qualifies as an accredited investor?","choices":{"A":"An individual with $150,000 annual income for the past two years","B":"A trust with $3 million in assets and a sophisticated trustee","C":"A family office with $4 million in assets under management","D":"A private business development company"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Private business development companies (BDCs) are specifically listed as accredited investors under Regulation D. Individual income threshold is $200,000 ($300,000 joint). Trusts need $5 million in assets (or all grantors must be accredited). Family offices need $5 million in assets under management.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv25","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When opening a brokerage account, which document requires customers to resolve disputes through FINRA rather than civil court?","choices":{"A":"Customer agreement/new account form","B":"Margin agreement","C":"Options agreement","D":"Pre-dispute arbitration agreement"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The pre-dispute arbitration agreement requires customers to submit disputes to FINRA arbitration rather than filing lawsuits in civil court. This is typically a separate signed document or highlighted clause. It protects firms from potentially expensive jury trials while providing customers with a faster, less costly resolution process.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv26","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 75-year-old IRA owner was required to take a $15,000 RMD but only withdrew $7,250. Under current IRS rules, what is the excise tax penalty if the shortfall is corrected promptly?","choices":{"A":"$3,875 with no reduction possible","B":"$1,550 if corrected within the correction window","C":"$775 if corrected within the correction window","D":"No penalty if corrected before year-end"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The RMD shortfall is $7,750 ($15,000 - $7,250). Under SECURE 2.0, the excise tax was reduced from 50% to 25%, making it $1,937.50. If the shortfall is corrected within the correction window (generally within 2 years), the penalty is further reduced to 10%, or approximately $775.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv27","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When applying FINRA's 5% markup policy, which factor is LEAST important in determining a reasonable markup?","choices":{"A":"The type of security and its availability","B":"The dollar amount of the transaction","C":"The customer's investment experience","D":"The pattern of markups by the firm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The 5% policy considers: (1) type of security, (2) availability/price, (3) dollar amount, (4) disclosure, (5) pattern of markups. The customer's investment experience is NOT a factor in determining fair markups - it relates to suitability, not pricing fairness.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv28","section":"Suitability","stem":"An investor with an aggressive growth objective would find which investment LEAST suitable?","choices":{"A":"Small-cap emerging market fund","B":"Sector technology ETF","C":"Large-cap dividend growth fund","D":"Leveraged index fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A large-cap dividend growth fund focuses on established companies paying dividends - this is a conservative to moderate strategy, not aggressive growth. Small-cap, sector, and leveraged funds all offer more aggressive growth potential with higher volatility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv29","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"When Company A merges with Company B and Company A shareholders will receive Company B stock, which SEC rule requires registration of the shares offered in the merger?","choices":{"A":"Rule 144","B":"Rule 144A","C":"Rule 145","D":"Rule 147"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Rule 145 requires registration of securities offered in mergers, acquisitions, and reclassifications where shareholders must approve the transaction. The shares offered to the acquired company's shareholders are considered a public offering requiring registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["securities-act-1933","sec"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv31","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which municipal bond carries the LOWEST default risk due to federal government backing?","choices":{"A":"Public Housing Authority bond backed by HUD","B":"General obligation bond","C":"Industrial development revenue bond","D":"Airport revenue bond"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Public Housing Authority (PHA) bonds backed by HUD contracts have the lowest default risk because they carry the full faith and credit of the U.S. government. This federal backing makes them safer than even general obligation bonds backed only by local taxing authority.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv32","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"The Super Display Book (SDBK) electronic order routing system is used on which exchange?","choices":{"A":"NASDAQ","B":"CBOE","C":"NYSE","D":"OTC Bulletin Board"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Super Display Book (SDBK) is the NYSE's electronic order delivery and reporting system. It routes orders directly to trading posts and handles the vast majority of NYSE orders electronically.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market","order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv33","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following would result in statutory disqualification from FINRA membership?","choices":{"A":"Parking violation 6 months ago","B":"Felony assault conviction 8 years ago","C":"Civil lawsuit for breach of contract","D":"Late filing of Form U4 update"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A felony conviction within the past 10 years results in statutory disqualification. The type of felony does not matter - any felony (not just securities-related) within 10 years disqualifies. Misdemeanors and civil matters generally do not cause disqualification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv34","section":"Options","stem":"An investor establishes a calendar spread: long December 50 calls and short October 50 calls. The investor profits MOST when:","choices":{"A":"Both options expire worthless","B":"The stock price moves significantly in either direction","C":"Time value erodes faster on the short-term option","D":"The spread narrows as expiration approaches"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a calendar spread, the investor is long the far-month option and short the near-month option. Maximum profit occurs when the stock stays near the strike price and time decay (theta) erodes the short-term option faster, widening the spread value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","call-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv35","section":"Economics","stem":"If the Consumer Price Index increases by 12% over one year, which statement about fixed-income investments is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Bond prices will generally increase","B":"Fixed-rate preferred stock dividends will have more purchasing power","C":"Fixed-rate preferred stock dividends will have less purchasing power than common stock dividends","D":"TIPS will provide negative real returns"},"answer":"C","explanation":"High inflation (12% CPI increase) reduces the purchasing power of fixed payments. Preferred stock pays fixed dividends that cannot increase, while common stock dividends may be raised. Thus, preferred holders lose more purchasing power than common holders who may receive dividend increases.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["economic-indicators","preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv36","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which type of brokerage account permits the customer to borrow funds from the broker-dealer to purchase securities?","choices":{"A":"Cash account","B":"Fee-based advisory account","C":"Margin account","D":"Custodial UTMA account"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A margin account allows customers to borrow money from the broker-dealer (using securities as collateral) to purchase additional securities. Cash accounts require full payment. Fee-based and custodial accounts can be either cash or margin but the margin feature is what enables borrowing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["margin-accounts","account-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv37","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Form 1099-B reports all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Proceeds from the sale of securities","B":"Proceeds from redemption of mutual fund shares","C":"Dividend payments received","D":"Cost basis information for covered securities"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Form 1099-B reports proceeds from sales and redemptions of securities, plus cost basis for covered securities. Dividend payments are reported on Form 1099-DIV, not 1099-B. Interest is reported on 1099-INT.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv38","section":"Options","stem":"An investor writes a covered call for $400 premium. The option is later closed with a closing purchase at $150. The $250 difference is treated as:","choices":{"A":"Ordinary income","B":"Tax-free return of capital","C":"Short-term or long-term capital gain depending on holding period","D":"Dividend income"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When an option writer closes a position, the difference between premium received and closing cost is a capital gain or loss. For options, the holding period determines short-term vs. long-term treatment. Listed options held under one year are short-term capital gains.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv39","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer calls and says \"Buy 100 shares of ABC whenever you think the price is right today.\" Executing this order:","choices":{"A":"Does NOT require a power of attorney since the customer specified the security and quantity","B":"Requires a discretionary trading authorization","C":"Cannot be executed without prior written principal approval","D":"Is prohibited under FINRA rules"},"answer":"A","explanation":"This is NOT a discretionary order because the customer specified the security (ABC), action (buy), and amount (100 shares). Only time and price are left to the representative. Discretion over time and price alone does not require a power of attorney or trading authorization.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv40","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative has a dispute with their firm over unpaid bonus compensation. This dispute must be resolved through:","choices":{"A":"Civil litigation in state court","B":"SEC enforcement action","C":"State securities administrator","D":"FINRA Code of Arbitration Procedure"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Employment disputes between registered representatives and their member firms, including compensation disputes, must be resolved through FINRA's Code of Arbitration Procedure. This is mandatory arbitration, not optional civil litigation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv41","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under FINRA Rule 2210, communications sent to banks, insurance companies, and registered investment companies are classified as:","choices":{"A":"Retail communications","B":"Correspondence","C":"Public appearances","D":"Institutional communications"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Institutional communications are those distributed exclusively to institutional investors, which include banks, insurance companies, registered investment companies, and any entity with $50 million+ in assets. Different approval and filing requirements apply than for retail communications.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv42","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which statement about Collateralized Mortgage Obligations (CMOs) is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"CMOs eliminate prepayment risk entirely","B":"All CMO tranches have identical risk characteristics","C":"CMOs are guaranteed by the U.S. Treasury","D":"Complex CMO tranches may face significant liquidity risk"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Complex CMO tranches (like Z-tranches, inverse floaters, and residuals) may face significant liquidity risk because they are difficult to value and have limited secondary market trading. CMOs redistribute (not eliminate) prepayment risk among tranches.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv43","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A convertible bond trading at $870 is convertible into 100 shares of common stock. What is the parity price of the stock?","choices":{"A":"$8.70","B":"$87.00","C":"$100.00","D":"$870.00"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Parity price is the stock price at which conversion equals the bond price. Parity = Bond Price / Conversion Ratio = $870 / 100 shares = $8.70. At this stock price, converting the bond yields the same value as selling the bond.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv44","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a straddle: long 1 XYZ Nov 70 call at $4 and long 1 XYZ Nov 70 put at $3.50. At which stock price would the investor NOT profit?","choices":{"A":"$58","B":"$72.50","C":"$78","D":"$60"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Total premium = $7.50. Breakevens: 70 + 7.50 = $77.50 (upside) and 70 - 7.50 = $62.50 (downside). At $72.50, the call has $2.50 intrinsic value, which is less than the $7.50 total cost. The investor loses $5.00 per share at $72.50.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv46","section":"Options","stem":"A yield-based call option on the 10-year Treasury yield has a strike of 45 and is trading at a premium of 7.5. What is the dollar value of the premium?","choices":{"A":"$75","B":"$450","C":"$750","D":"$7,500"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Yield-based options use a $100 multiplier. Premium value = quoted premium x $100 = 7.5 x $100 = $750. The strike of 45 represents a yield of 4.5%, and the premium is quoted in index points.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv47","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A married couple files jointly. The husband has $150,000 earned income; the wife has no earned income. Both are under age 50. What is the maximum combined IRA contribution for 2024?","choices":{"A":"$7,000 for husband only","B":"$14,000 combined ($7,000 each)","C":"$8,000 for husband only","D":"$16,000 combined ($8,000 each)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"With a spousal IRA, a non-working spouse can contribute up to the annual maximum if the working spouse has sufficient earned income. For 2024, under age 50 = $7,000 each. Both spouses can contribute $7,000, for a combined $14,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv48","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A California resident purchases a California municipal bond. The interest income is:","choices":{"A":"Subject to federal and state income tax","B":"Exempt from federal tax but subject to California state tax","C":"Subject to federal tax but exempt from California state tax","D":"Exempt from federal, California state, and local income taxes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Municipal bond interest is exempt from federal income tax. Additionally, most states exempt interest from bonds issued within the state from state and local taxes. A California resident with a California muni bond receives \"triple tax-exempt\" interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv49","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns 100 shares of XYZ at $160 per share. After a 20% stock dividend, what is the investor's adjusted cost basis per share?","choices":{"A":"$160.00 per share (no change)","B":"$128.00 per share","C":"$133.33 per share","D":"$192.00 per share"},"answer":"C","explanation":"After a 20% stock dividend, the investor has 120 shares (100 x 1.20). The total cost basis remains $16,000 (100 x $160). New cost basis per share = $16,000 / 120 shares = $133.33 per share.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv50","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A fixed annuity guarantees a stated rate of return. Which risk does the INSURANCE COMPANY bear when issuing fixed annuities?","choices":{"A":"Market risk passed to the annuitant","B":"Mortality risk only","C":"Inflation risk for the annuitant","D":"Reinvestment risk in the general account"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The insurance company bears reinvestment risk because it guarantees a fixed return but invests in its general account where rates may decline. If the company cannot earn the guaranteed rate, it absorbs the loss. The annuitant does NOT bear investment risk with fixed annuities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv51","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A portfolio manager holds a stock with a beta of 0.3. Compared to the overall market, this stock would be expected to:","choices":{"A":"Outperform in a bull market and outperform in a bear market","B":"Underperform in a bull market and outperform in a bear market","C":"Outperform in a bull market and underperform in a bear market","D":"Match market performance regardless of direction"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A beta below 1.0 indicates the stock is less volatile than the market. A beta of 0.3 means the stock moves only 30% as much as the market. In rising markets, it will rise less (underperform), and in falling markets, it will fall less (outperform/lose less).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv52","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A margin account has $8,000 in SMA (Special Memorandum Account). Under Regulation T, how much in additional marginable securities can the customer purchase?","choices":{"A":"$4,000","B":"$8,000","C":"$16,000","D":"$32,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under Regulation T, the initial margin requirement is 50%. SMA represents buying power, and the customer can purchase securities worth 2x the SMA balance. With $8,000 SMA, buying power is $8,000 x 2 = $16,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv53","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"An issuer agrees to a best efforts underwriting where the offering will be cancelled if less than $5 million is raised, but up to $15 million may be sold. This arrangement is called:","choices":{"A":"All-or-none","B":"Stand-by commitment","C":"Mini-maxi","D":"Firm commitment"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A mini-maxi underwriting has both a minimum threshold (mini) that must be met for the offering to proceed and a maximum amount (maxi) that can be sold. If the minimum is not reached, all funds are returned to investors.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv54","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A municipality issues bonds to fund sidewalk improvements. Only property owners in the affected district will be assessed to pay the debt service. These bonds are:","choices":{"A":"General obligation bonds","B":"Revenue bonds","C":"Industrial development bonds","D":"Special assessment bonds"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Special assessment bonds are repaid through assessments on the specific properties that benefit from the improvement. Unlike GO bonds backed by general taxing power, these are paid only by property owners in the benefited area.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv55","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which statement regarding bond interest taxation is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Treasury bond interest is exempt from federal income tax","B":"Municipal bond interest is always exempt from state income tax","C":"Corporate bond interest is taxed as ordinary income at all levels","D":"Zero-coupon municipal bond accretion is federally taxable"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Corporate bond interest is fully taxable as ordinary income at federal, state, and local levels. Treasury interest is exempt from state/local (not federal). Municipal bond interest is federally exempt but may be subject to state tax if from an out-of-state issuer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds","municipal-bonds","government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv56","section":"Options","stem":"An investor is short a Dec $45 call on XYZ stock. To create a bull call spread, the investor must:","choices":{"A":"Buy a Dec $40 call","B":"Buy a Dec $50 call","C":"Sell a Dec $40 put","D":"Buy a Dec $45 put"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A bull call spread requires being long a call with a lower strike price and short a call with a higher strike price on the same underlying. Since the investor is already short the $45 call, buying a Dec $40 call creates a bull call spread.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","call-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv57","section":"Options","stem":"At expiration, a call option with a strike price of $50 is in-the-money with the underlying stock at $52. If the option holder takes no action, the OCC will:","choices":{"A":"Allow the option to expire worthless","B":"Request instructions from the holder","C":"Automatically exercise the option","D":"Roll the option to the next expiration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The OCC automatically exercises options that are in-the-money by $0.01 or more at expiration unless the holder provides contrary instructions. This is called \"exercise by exception\" and protects holders from losing intrinsic value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv58","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"For a callable bond trading at a premium, which yield relationship is FALSE?","choices":{"A":"Current yield is less than coupon rate","B":"Yield to maturity is less than current yield","C":"Yield to call is less than yield to maturity","D":"Coupon rate exceeds current market rates"},"answer":"A","explanation":"For a premium bond, current yield is HIGHER than YTM (not less than coupon rate). The relationship is: Coupon rate > Current yield > YTM > YTC. Current yield = annual coupon / market price, which is lower than coupon rate when price exceeds par.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["bond-yields","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv59","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In 2025, a 45-year-old individual with $6,000 in earned income can contribute a maximum of how much to a traditional IRA?","choices":{"A":"$6,000","B":"$7,000","C":"$8,000","D":"$14,000"},"answer":"A","explanation":"IRA contributions are limited to the lesser of the annual maximum ($7,000 for those under 50 in 2025) or 100% of earned income. Since this individual only has $6,000 in earned income, the maximum contribution is limited to $6,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv60","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Regulation S-P was enacted primarily to:","choices":{"A":"Establish margin requirements for securities transactions","B":"Protect customer nonpublic personal information from unauthorized disclosure","C":"Define accredited investor qualifications","D":"Regulate the sale of penny stocks"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Regulation S-P (Privacy of Consumer Financial Information) requires financial institutions to protect customer privacy by limiting disclosure of nonpublic personal information and providing customers the right to opt out of certain information sharing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv61","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"In which type of underwriting does the investment banker purchase the entire issue from the issuer and bear the risk of resale?","choices":{"A":"All-or-none","B":"Best efforts","C":"Stand-by","D":"Firm commitment"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a firm commitment underwriting, the underwriter purchases the entire issue from the issuer (becoming a dealer), assuming the risk that it may not sell all securities. The issuer is guaranteed to receive the agreed-upon proceeds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv62","section":"Options","stem":"An investor establishes a bear put spread by buying a Jan $60 put for $6 and selling a Jan $55 put for $3. At expiration with the stock at $57, what is the investor's result?","choices":{"A":"$200 loss","B":"$300 profit","C":"$500 profit","D":"$800 loss"},"answer":"A","explanation":"At $57, the long $60 put has $3 intrinsic value and the short $55 put expires worthless. Net result: $3 received from exercise - $6 paid + $3 received = $0 intrinsic - $3 net debit = $3 loss x 100 = $300 loss. Actually: $3 - $3 = $0 profit from options, but net debit was $3, so $200 loss.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv63","section":"Options","stem":"An investor writes a straddle, selling a $50 call for $4 and a $50 put for $3. Which price would result in a LOSS for this position?","choices":{"A":"$47","B":"$53","C":"$55","D":"$58"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Total premium received is $7, so breakeven points are $43 and $57. At $58, the call is $8 ITM, exceeding the $7 premium received. The investor loses $1 per share ($8 intrinsic value - $7 premium = $1 loss x 100 = $100 loss).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","call-options","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv64","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"When interest rates rise significantly, how are Principal-Only (PO) CMO tranches typically affected?","choices":{"A":"Market value increases due to higher yields","B":"Prepayment speeds increase, benefiting PO holders","C":"Market value declines as prepayments slow","D":"No effect since principal is guaranteed"},"answer":"C","explanation":"PO (Principal-Only) tranches benefit from faster prepayments. When rates rise, homeowners refinance less, prepayments slow, and PO holders receive principal more slowly than expected. This negative convexity causes PO values to decline sharply when rates rise.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv65","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under Regulation S-P, which requirement applies to the customer opt-out process for sharing information with non-affiliated third parties?","choices":{"A":"Customers must opt out in writing within 30 days","B":"Opt-out must be renewed annually by the customer","C":"The firm must wait 60 days before sharing after opt-out notice","D":"The opt-out method must be simple and easy to use"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Regulation S-P requires that firms provide a reasonable means for customers to opt out of information sharing. The method must be simple and easy to use - firms cannot make the process difficult or burdensome.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv66","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which statement about feasibility studies for municipal revenue bonds is FALSE?","choices":{"A":"They project revenues and expenses for the facility","B":"They must be completed by the municipality's treasurer","C":"They assess the economic viability of the project","D":"They are typically prepared by independent consultants"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Feasibility studies are typically prepared by independent consulting engineers or financial consultants, NOT the treasurer. The study provides an objective third-party assessment of whether the project can generate sufficient revenue to cover debt service.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv67","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In a short margin account, how is equity calculated?","choices":{"A":"Long market value minus debit balance","B":"Debit balance minus short market value","C":"Credit balance minus short market value","D":"Short market value minus credit balance"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Short margin equity = Credit balance - Short market value (SMV). The credit balance represents sale proceeds plus required margin deposit. When the SMV rises, equity decreases; when SMV falls, equity increases.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv68","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor buys a municipal bond at an original issue discount of $920. After accreting $40, the adjusted cost basis is $960. If sold for $1,030, what are the tax consequences?","choices":{"A":"$110 capital gain","B":"$70 capital gain only","C":"$40 tax-exempt interest, $70 capital gain","D":"$110 tax-exempt interest"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For OID municipal bonds, the accreted amount ($40) is tax-exempt interest. The capital gain is calculated from the accreted cost basis: $1,030 - $960 = $70 capital gain. The $40 accretion was already reported as tax-exempt interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["municipal-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv69","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"When a mutual fund shareholder redeems shares, the price received is based on the:","choices":{"A":"Public offering price (POP)","B":"Net asset value (NAV)","C":"Previous day's closing price","D":"Average of bid and ask prices"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Mutual fund shares are redeemed at NAV (net asset value), which is the bid price. The NAV is calculated daily by dividing net assets by shares outstanding. There is no sales charge on redemptions (though CDSCs may apply to some share classes).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv70","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following describes a Eurobond?\nI. Denominated in a currency other than the currency of the country where issued\nII. Subject to SEC registration requirements\nIII. Typically issued in bearer form\nIV. Traded in the international bond market","choices":{"A":"I and II only","B":"II and III only","C":"I, II, and IV only","D":"I, III, and IV only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Eurobonds are denominated in a currency different from the country of issuance, traditionally issued in bearer form, and traded internationally. They are NOT registered with the SEC as they are issued outside U.S. jurisdiction.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv71","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"A selling group member participating in a new issue offering receives compensation in the form of:","choices":{"A":"The manager's fee","B":"The underwriting spread","C":"The reallowance","D":"The selling concession"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Selling group members receive only the selling concession, which is a portion of the underwriting spread. They do not receive the manager's fee (paid to lead manager) or the full spread (which goes to syndicate members who assume risk).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv72","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under FINRA communications rules, which of the following would be classified as retail communication?","choices":{"A":"A password-protected website accessible to 45 retail clients","B":"An email sent to 20 retail customers","C":"A presentation to institutional investors only","D":"A letter addressed to a single prospective client"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Retail communication is any written communication distributed to more than 25 retail investors within a 30-day period. A website accessible to 45 retail clients exceeds this threshold, making it retail communication requiring principal pre-approval.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv73","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which statement about matching investments to client profiles is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Clients with low liquidity needs may be suitable for direct participation programs (DPPs)","B":"High-risk tolerance clients should only invest in government bonds","C":"Short time horizons are ideal for aggressive growth strategies","D":"Conservative investors should maximize exposure to small-cap stocks"},"answer":"A","explanation":"DPPs (limited partnerships) are illiquid investments suitable for clients who do not need immediate access to their funds. High liquidity needs would make DPPs unsuitable. Time horizon, risk tolerance, and investment objectives must all align with recommendations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv74","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A municipality issues bonds backed solely by revenues from hotel occupancy taxes. These are classified as:","choices":{"A":"General obligation bonds","B":"Revenue bonds","C":"Special tax bonds","D":"Tax anticipation notes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Special tax bonds are secured by a specific tax source, such as hotel/motel taxes, gasoline taxes, or sin taxes. They differ from GO bonds (backed by general taxing power) and revenue bonds (backed by project income).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv75","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which retail communication is NOT exempt from the requirement to be filed with FINRA within 10 business days of first use?","choices":{"A":"A previously filed communication being used again","B":"A communication from a firm that has filed similar materials for 3 years","C":"A communication solely about money market funds","D":"A communication from a firm in its first year of FINRA membership"},"answer":"D","explanation":"New FINRA member firms (in their first year) must file retail communications at least 10 business days BEFORE first use (pre-filing requirement). This is more stringent than established firms, which may file within 10 days of first use for certain materials.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv76","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A client seeks both current income and potential capital appreciation while minimizing exposure to stock market volatility. Which investment would BEST meet these objectives?","choices":{"A":"Growth stock mutual fund","B":"High-yield corporate bond fund","C":"Money market fund","D":"20-year 6.5% convertible debenture"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A convertible debenture provides current income through interest payments while offering potential capital appreciation through conversion to common stock. Unlike direct stock ownership, the bond provides downside protection through its fixed-income characteristics, helping minimize market risk exposure while still participating in equity upside through the conversion feature.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv77","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A client places a sell stop order at $45 for XYZ stock. The stock is currently trading at $48. What will happen if the stock price rises to $52?","choices":{"A":"The order will remain open until the stop price is reached","B":"The order will be executed immediately at $52","C":"The order will be canceled automatically","D":"The order will convert to a limit order at $45"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A sell stop order is placed below the current market price and is only triggered when the stock trades at or below the stop price. Since the stock rose to $52 (above the $45 stop price), the order remains open and unexecuted. The order will only be triggered if the stock price falls to $45 or below.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv78","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, which of the following would be classified as a penny stock?","choices":{"A":"NYSE-listed stock trading at $4.50 per share","B":"NASDAQ Global Market stock trading at $3.75 per share","C":"OTC stock not listed on a national exchange trading at $4.25 per share","D":"S&P 500 component trading at $2.50 per share"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Penny stocks are generally defined as securities trading below $5 per share that are NOT listed on a national securities exchange (NYSE, NASDAQ). The OTC stock trading at $4.25 qualifies as a penny stock because it is both under $5 and not listed on a national exchange. Stocks listed on major exchanges are exempt from penny stock rules regardless of price.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv79","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"When a security is described as \"dual listed,\" this means that:","choices":{"A":"The security trades in both the primary and secondary markets","B":"The security is listed on two different national exchanges simultaneously","C":"The security has both common and preferred classes outstanding","D":"The security can be purchased with cash or on margin"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Dual listing refers to a security being listed on two different national securities exchanges at the same time, such as both the NYSE and NASDAQ. This provides greater liquidity and visibility for the security. It does not refer to primary vs. secondary markets, share classes, or margin eligibility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv80","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following statements about preferred stock is INCORRECT?","choices":{"A":"Preferred stockholders have priority over common stockholders in liquidation","B":"Preferred stock typically pays a fixed dividend rate","C":"Cumulative preferred stock accumulates unpaid dividends","D":"Preferred stock prices rise when interest rates increase"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This statement is incorrect because preferred stock prices have an inverse relationship with interest rates, similar to bonds. When interest rates rise, preferred stock prices typically fall because the fixed dividend becomes less attractive compared to newly issued securities with higher yields. The other statements are all accurate characteristics of preferred stock.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock","interest-rates"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv81","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor wants to purchase an investment-grade corporate bond. Which of the following bonds would meet this criterion?","choices":{"A":"15-year CCC+ rated secured bond","B":"10-year BB rated convertible bond","C":"20-year B+ rated debenture","D":"25-year BBB- rated corporate debenture"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Investment-grade bonds are rated BBB-/Baa3 or higher by major rating agencies. The 25-year BBB- rated debenture is the only investment-grade option. CCC+, BB, and B+ ratings are all below investment grade (speculative/junk) regardless of the bond type or maturity. The BBB- rating is the lowest investment-grade rating.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-ratings","corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv82","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following is a federally sponsored agency that provides financing for agricultural operations?","choices":{"A":"Federal National Mortgage Association (Fannie Mae)","B":"Federal Farm Credit System","C":"Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (Freddie Mac)","D":"Government National Mortgage Association (Ginnie Mae)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Federal Farm Credit System (FFCS) is a federally sponsored agency that provides financing specifically for agricultural operations, including loans to farmers, ranchers, and rural homeowners. Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, and Ginnie Mae are all focused on the housing/mortgage market rather than agriculture.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv83","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An investment club that includes a registered representative as a member wants to purchase shares in an IPO. Under FINRA rules, this would be permitted:","choices":{"A":"Only if all members are registered representatives","B":"Only if the registered representative owns less than 10% of the club","C":"Only if the IPO is for a technology company","D":"Under no circumstances"},"answer":"B","explanation":"FINRA Rule 5130 restricts industry insiders from purchasing IPO shares. However, an investment club may purchase IPO shares if restricted persons (such as registered representatives) own less than 10% of the club. This de minimis exemption allows participation while preventing significant insider advantage in hot IPOs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv84","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"An investor seeking steady income from oil and gas investments with lower risk would most likely invest in a program that focuses on:","choices":{"A":"Exploratory (wildcat) drilling","B":"Development drilling near proven reserves","C":"Combination programs with mixed objectives","D":"Acquiring existing producing wells (stripper wells)"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Income programs that acquire existing producing wells (including stripper wells) offer the lowest risk and provide steady income because the wells are already producing oil or gas. Exploratory drilling has the highest risk as it searches for new reserves. Development drilling has moderate risk, while combination programs mix various risk levels.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv85","section":"Options","stem":"An investor establishes the following position: Buy 10 ABC Jan 50 puts at 7, Sell 10 ABC Jan 45 puts at 3. At expiration, ABC stock is trading at $42. What is the investor's gain or loss?","choices":{"A":"$1,000 loss","B":"$1,000 gain","C":"$4,000 loss","D":"$4,000 gain"},"answer":"B","explanation":"This is a bear put spread (debit spread). Net premium paid: (7 - 3) x 10 x 100 = $4,000 debit. At expiration with stock at $42: The 50 puts are worth $8 (50 - 42), the 45 puts are worth $3 (45 - 42). Value at expiration: ($8 - $3) x 10 x 100 = $5,000. Profit = $5,000 - $4,000 = $1,000 gain.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv86","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A customer purchases Treasury bonds on Thursday. When will the trade settle?","choices":{"A":"Friday (T+1)","B":"Monday (T+2)","C":"Tuesday (T+3)","D":"The following Thursday (T+5)"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Treasury securities (T-bills, T-notes, and T-bonds) settle on T+1, meaning one business day after the trade date. A Thursday trade settles on Friday. This is different from corporate and municipal securities, which settle on T+2 (formerly T+3).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["settlement","government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv87","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"In a firm commitment underwriting, the public offering price is $25, the underwriting spread is $1.50, and the selling concession is $0.85. A selling group member (not in the syndicate) sells 1,000 shares. What is the selling group member's total compensation?","choices":{"A":"$650","B":"$850","C":"$1,500","D":"$2,350"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Selling group members receive only the selling concession, not the full spread. The selling concession is $0.85 per share. For 1,000 shares: $0.85 x 1,000 = $850. The remainder of the spread goes to the syndicate members and managing underwriter.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv88","section":"Economics","stem":"The federal income tax system in the United States is characterized as:","choices":{"A":"Regressive, where lower earners pay a higher percentage","B":"Flat, where all earners pay the same percentage","C":"Proportional, where rates increase with income brackets","D":"Progressive, where higher earners pay a higher percentage of income"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The U.S. federal income tax system is progressive, meaning tax rates increase as taxable income increases through various tax brackets. Higher earners pay a higher marginal tax rate on income above certain thresholds. This is different from a regressive tax (like sales tax) or a flat tax where everyone pays the same rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv89","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"All of the following are characteristics of a no-load mutual fund EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"No front-end sales charge","B":"Professional portfolio management","C":"Diversification across multiple securities","D":"No sales charge at purchase or redemption"},"answer":"D","explanation":"While no-load funds do not charge front-end or back-end sales loads, the statement that there is \"no sales charge at purchase or redemption\" is misleading because the question asks for the exception. No-load funds may still charge 12b-1 fees (up to 0.25% to remain no-load). All mutual funds, including no-load funds, offer professional management and diversification.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv90","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investor inherits stock that the decedent purchased for $500. On the date of death, the stock was worth $1,200. The investor sells the stock for $1,500 three months after inheriting it. What is the tax consequence?","choices":{"A":"$300 long-term capital gain","B":"$300 short-term capital gain","C":"$1,000 long-term capital gain","D":"$1,000 short-term capital gain"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Inherited securities receive a stepped-up cost basis equal to the fair market value at the date of death ($1,200) and are automatically considered long-term regardless of actual holding period. The gain is $1,500 - $1,200 = $300, and it is a long-term capital gain even though the heir only held the stock for three months.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv91","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Eurodollar deposits are BEST described as:","choices":{"A":"U.S. dollar deposits held in European Union banks only","B":"Foreign currency deposits held in U.S. banks","C":"U.S. dollar deposits held at banks outside the United States","D":"Euro currency deposits held anywhere in the world"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Eurodollars are U.S. dollar-denominated deposits held at banks outside the United States, not just in Europe despite the name. They can be held at any foreign bank or foreign branch of a U.S. bank. The term does not refer to the euro currency but rather to the historical origin of such deposits in European banks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv92","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following statements about U.S. government securities is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"They are subject to state and local income taxes","B":"They carry significant default risk","C":"They represent the largest and most liquid securities market in the world","D":"They are only available to institutional investors"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The U.S. government securities market is the largest and most liquid securities market in the world, with trillions of dollars trading daily. U.S. Treasury securities are exempt from state and local income taxes, carry virtually no default risk (backed by full faith and credit), and are available to all investors including individuals.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv93","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Which of the following statements about extended hours trading (pre-market and after-hours) is FALSE?","choices":{"A":"Broker-dealers are not required to provide additional disclosures about extended hours risks","B":"Liquidity is typically lower than during regular trading hours","C":"Price volatility may be greater than during regular hours","D":"Spreads between bid and ask prices are often wider"},"answer":"A","explanation":"This statement is FALSE. FINRA requires broker-dealers to disclose the unique risks of extended hours trading to customers, including lower liquidity, wider spreads, greater volatility, and the possibility that prices may not reflect the next day's opening prices. Customers must receive these disclosures before trading in extended hours sessions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv95","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A mutual fund that qualifies under Subchapter M of the Internal Revenue Code:","choices":{"A":"Must pay corporate income tax on all investment income","B":"Cannot distribute capital gains to shareholders","C":"Passes through taxation of income and gains to shareholders, avoiding double taxation","D":"Is exempt from all federal taxation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Subchapter M of the IRC provides the \"conduit\" or \"pipeline\" tax treatment for regulated investment companies (mutual funds). Qualifying funds that distribute at least 90% of their net investment income pass the tax liability to shareholders, avoiding double taxation at the corporate level. The fund itself is not taxed on distributed income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv96","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor wants growth potential, current income, and diversification across both stocks and bonds within a single investment. Which type of mutual fund would BEST suit this investor?","choices":{"A":"Sector fund","B":"Index fund","C":"Balanced fund","D":"Money market fund"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A balanced fund invests in both stocks (for growth) and bonds (for income), providing diversification across asset classes within a single investment. This combination addresses all three of the investor's objectives. Sector funds concentrate in one industry, index funds track a specific index, and money market funds focus on preservation with minimal growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv97","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"All of the following are characteristics of FINRA arbitration proceedings EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Decisions are final and binding","B":"Discovery is more limited than in court proceedings","C":"Hearings are open to the public","D":"The process is generally faster than litigation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"FINRA arbitration hearings are NOT open to the public; they are private proceedings. The other statements are accurate: arbitration decisions are final and binding with very limited grounds for appeal, discovery is more limited than in court, and the process is typically faster and less expensive than traditional litigation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv98","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A U.S. Treasury bond with interest payment dates of March 1 and September 1 is sold on August 15. How many days of accrued interest does the buyer owe the seller? (Assume a 30-day month)","choices":{"A":"164 days","B":"165 days","C":"167 days","D":"168 days"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Government bonds accrue interest using actual/actual day count. From the last payment date (March 1) to settlement: March (30 days remaining after March 1) + April (30) + May (30) + June (30) + July (30) + August 1-15 (15 days, up to but not including settlement) = 30 + 30 + 30 + 30 + 30 + 15 + 2 = 167 days. Note: Accrued interest is calculated up to but not including the settlement date.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["government-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv99","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"All of the following types of bonds are secured by specific collateral EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Mortgage bonds","B":"Equipment trust certificates","C":"Collateral trust bonds","D":"Bonds backed by the full faith and credit of the issuer"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Bonds backed by \"full faith and credit\" are unsecured obligations backed by the general creditworthiness and taxing power of the issuer, not by specific collateral. Mortgage bonds are secured by real property, equipment trust certificates by equipment (rolling stock), and collateral trust bonds by securities owned by the issuer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv100","section":"Options","stem":"An investor establishes a bear put spread by buying a put with a strike price of $75 for a premium of $8 and selling a put with a strike price of $65 for a premium of $3. What is the breakeven point for this spread?","choices":{"A":"$67","B":"$68","C":"$70","D":"$73"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a bear put spread (debit spread), the breakeven equals the higher strike price minus the net premium paid. Net premium = $8 paid - $3 received = $5 net debit. Breakeven = $75 - $5 = $70. At $70, the long put is worth $5 (75 - 70), which exactly offsets the $5 net premium paid.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv102","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A municipality wants to finance a new government building. The financing will be secured by lease payments the municipality makes to occupy the building. Which type of security best describes this arrangement?","choices":{"A":"General obligation bond","B":"Revenue bond","C":"Certificate of Participation (COP)","D":"Tax anticipation note"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Certificates of Participation (COPs) represent an interest in lease payments made by a municipality. Unlike GO bonds backed by taxing power or revenue bonds backed by project revenues, COPs are backed by the lease payments the municipality makes as the tenant of the financed property.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv103","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor plans to hold mutual fund shares for only 18 months before liquidating for a home purchase. Which share class would typically be MOST appropriate?","choices":{"A":"Class C shares with level loads","B":"Class A shares with front-end loads","C":"Class B shares with declining CDSCs","D":"Class R shares for retirement plans"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Class C shares are most suitable for short-term investors (typically under 3-4 years) because they have no or minimal front-end loads and lower ongoing expenses compared to paying a large upfront load on Class A shares for a short holding period. Class B CDSC schedules typically extend 5-7 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv105","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Regarding original issue discount (OID) bonds, which statement is INCORRECT?","choices":{"A":"Municipal OID bonds must be accreted for tax purposes","B":"Corporate OID bonds generate phantom income that is taxable annually","C":"Newly issued corporate discount bonds do NOT need to be accreted","D":"The accretion amount increases the investor's cost basis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Newly issued corporate discount (OID) bonds MUST be accreted for tax purposes. The annual accretion is taxable as ordinary income (phantom income) even though no cash is received. This is incorrect - all OID bonds, whether corporate or municipal, require accretion.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv106","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A registered representative wants to help a close friend raise capital for a new restaurant venture by soliciting investments from other clients. According to FINRA rules, what is required?","choices":{"A":"The representative must resign from the broker-dealer first","B":"This activity is prohibited under all circumstances","C":"The firm must approve and maintain records of the activity","D":"Only accredited investors may be solicited"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under FINRA rules, registered representatives may engage in private securities transactions (selling away), but MUST provide prior written notice to their firm. If the activity involves compensation, the firm must approve it and supervise the transactions as if they were executed through the firm. Records must be maintained.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv107","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor with $250,000 plans to invest in a mutual fund and hold for 15+ years. Which share class typically offers the BEST value for this scenario?","choices":{"A":"Class A shares with front-end load and breakpoint discounts","B":"Class B shares with contingent deferred sales charge","C":"Class C shares with level loads","D":"All share classes have identical costs over time"},"answer":"A","explanation":"For long-term investors with significant capital, Class A shares are typically most cost-effective. The large investment qualifies for breakpoint discounts reducing the front-end load, and ongoing 12b-1 fees are lower than other classes. Over 15+ years, the cumulative savings on annual expenses outweigh the initial load.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv108","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer's account has been frozen due to a previous free-riding violation. Which activity is the customer permitted to perform?","choices":{"A":"Buy securities using the proceeds from a same-day sale","B":"Sell securities currently held in the account","C":"Purchase securities only if cash is deposited prior to the order","D":"Trade on margin with proper disclosure"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When an account is frozen (typically for 90 days after a free-riding violation), the customer may only purchase securities if cash is already in the account BEFORE the order is placed. They cannot buy securities with the intent to pay later or use sale proceeds from the same day.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv113","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor purchases a Treasury bond quoted at 104:24. What is the cost per bond (excluding any fees)?","choices":{"A":"$1,042.40","B":"$1,044.75","C":"$1,047.50","D":"$1,048.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Treasury bonds are quoted in 32nds. 104:24 means 104 and 24/32 percent of par. Calculation: 104 + (24/32) = 104 + 0.75 = 104.75% of $1,000 par = $1,047.50 per bond.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["government-bonds","bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv114","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which investor profile is BEST suited for Class B mutual fund shares?","choices":{"A":"Investor with 7+ year time horizon and limited initial capital","B":"Short-term trader needing liquidity within 2 years","C":"Investor with $500,000 seeking maximum breakpoint discounts","D":"Day trader requiring immediate redemption capability"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Class B shares suit investors with longer time horizons (to avoid CDSC) and less capital (no upfront load). The CDSC typically declines to zero over 5-7 years, and shares often convert to Class A. Investors with large sums benefit more from Class A breakpoints.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv115","section":"Options","stem":"A VIX put option is quoted at 2.75. What is the total premium for one contract?","choices":{"A":"$27.50","B":"$275.00","C":"$2,750.00","D":"$2.75"},"answer":"B","explanation":"VIX options have a multiplier of 100, like standard equity options. Premium calculation: 2.75 x 100 = $275 per contract. The VIX (CBOE Volatility Index) options are cash-settled and based on expected S&P 500 volatility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv116","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a straddle: long 1 XYZ May 70 call at $6 and long 1 XYZ May 70 put at $5. What are the breakeven points?","choices":{"A":"$64.00 and $76.00","B":"$59.00 and $81.00","C":"$65.00 and $75.00","D":"$60.00 and $80.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a long straddle, total premium paid = $6 + $5 = $11. Upper breakeven = Strike + Total Premium = $70 + $11 = $81. Lower breakeven = Strike - Total Premium = $70 - $11 = $59. The stock must move beyond these points for profit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv117","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A municipal bond trade is executed on Thursday. When does regular-way settlement occur?","choices":{"A":"Friday (next business day)","B":"Monday (3 business days later)","C":"The same day (cash settlement)","D":"Tuesday (4 business days later)"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Municipal bonds settle regular-way on T+1 (trade date plus one business day). A trade executed on Thursday settles on Friday. This is the same settlement cycle as corporate bonds and equities following the SEC's 2024 rule change.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["municipal-bonds","settlement"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv118","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"A real estate limited partnership (RELP) investor may receive tax credits from investing in which type of property?","choices":{"A":"Commercial office buildings","B":"Luxury residential developments","C":"Government-subsidized low-income housing","D":"Raw land held for appreciation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax credits are available for investments in government-assisted or low-income housing programs (Section 42 credits). These credits directly reduce tax liability dollar-for-dollar, unlike deductions. Commercial, luxury, and raw land investments do not generate similar tax credits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv122","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a long-term XYZ put and sells a short-term XYZ put, both with the same strike price. What type of position is this?","choices":{"A":"Bear put spread","B":"Bull put spread","C":"Horizontal (calendar/time) spread","D":"Diagonal spread"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When options have the same strike price but different expirations, it is a horizontal (calendar or time) spread. Since the long-term option costs more than the short-term, this is a debit spread. It is NOT a bull or bear spread - those require different strike prices (vertical spreads).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["options-strategies","put-options"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv123","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"According to odd-lot theory, when small investors increase their buying activity, what action would a contrarian investor consider?","choices":{"A":"Increase equity positions immediately","B":"Hold current positions unchanged","C":"Buy more aggressively than small investors","D":"Consider selling or shorting the market"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Odd-lot theory is a contrarian indicator suggesting that small (retail) investors are typically wrong at market extremes. When odd-lot purchases increase significantly, contrarian theory suggests the market may be near a top, indicating a potential selling or shorting opportunity.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["secondary-market"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-pv125","section":"Options","stem":"A British pound call option is quoted at 4.00 cents per unit. If the contract covers 10,000 British pounds, what is the total premium?","choices":{"A":"$40.00","B":"$400.00","C":"$4,000.00","D":"$4.00"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Currency option premiums are quoted in cents per unit. Total premium = 4.00 cents x 10,000 units = 40,000 cents = $400. British pound options typically have a contract size of 10,000 units. The quote of 4.00 means 4 cents per pound.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-pricing"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-001","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investor is concerned about market risk but wants to maximize potential returns. Which investment approach focuses on diversification to minimize risk while simultaneously increasing expected return?","choices":{"A":"Modern portfolio theory","B":"Technical analysis","C":"Fundamental analysis","D":"Market timing"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Modern portfolio theory (MPT), developed by Harry Markowitz, focuses on diversification to minimize risk while maximizing expected return. The theory holds that the greater the diversification, the lower the portfolio risk and volatility. MPT demonstrates that investors can construct an \"efficient\" portfolio that provides the highest expected return for a given level of risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-002","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A client invests $500 in a mutual fund every month regardless of the share price. This systematic investment approach is called:","choices":{"A":"Market timing","B":"Value averaging","C":"Dollar-cost averaging","D":"Lump-sum investing"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Dollar-cost averaging (DCA) is an investment strategy where an investor invests the same dollar amount into the same investment at regular intervals, regardless of the share price. This approach results in buying more shares when prices are low and fewer shares when prices are high, potentially lowering the average cost per share over time when prices fluctuate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds","diversification"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-003","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which metric measures a security's volatility compared to the overall market?","choices":{"A":"Alpha","B":"Beta","C":"Sharpe ratio","D":"Standard deviation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Beta measures a security's volatility (systematic risk) relative to the overall market. A beta of 1.0 indicates the security moves in line with the market. A beta greater than 1.0 signifies higher volatility than the market, while a beta less than 1.0 indicates lower volatility. For example, a stock with a beta of 1.5 would be expected to rise 15% if the market rises 10%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-004","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which of the following best describes alpha in investment analysis?","choices":{"A":"The measure of systematic risk","B":"The risk-free rate of return","C":"The excess return compared to a benchmark","D":"The standard deviation of returns"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Alpha measures an investment's performance compared to a benchmark index, representing excess return. A positive alpha indicates the investment outperformed its benchmark after adjusting for risk, while a negative alpha indicates underperformance. Alpha is often used to evaluate portfolio manager skill - a manager who consistently generates positive alpha is adding value beyond market returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-005","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A client's strategic asset allocation calls for 60% stocks and 40% bonds. After strong equity market performance, the portfolio is now 70% stocks and 30% bonds. What action should be taken to rebalance the portfolio?","choices":{"A":"Buy more stocks to capitalize on momentum","B":"Sell stocks and buy bonds to restore the target allocation","C":"Do nothing - let the winners run","D":"Convert the entire portfolio to cash"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Portfolio rebalancing involves bringing the portfolio back to its target allocation. Since stocks have outperformed and now represent 70% of the portfolio (above the 60% target), the investor should sell a portion of stocks and use the proceeds to buy bonds to restore the 60/40 target allocation. This disciplined approach helps maintain the desired risk level.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-006","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"What is the primary difference between strategic asset allocation and tactical asset allocation?","choices":{"A":"Strategic uses stocks while tactical uses bonds","B":"Strategic is long-term based on investor goals; tactical involves short-term adjustments for market opportunities","C":"Tactical is less risky than strategic allocation","D":"Strategic allocation changes daily while tactical allocation never changes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Strategic asset allocation (SAA) establishes long-term target allocations based on the investor's goals, risk tolerance, and time horizon as defined in the investment policy statement. Tactical asset allocation (TAA) involves making short-term adjustments (typically lasting up to one year) to capitalize on specific market opportunities or conditions while staying within policy limits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-007","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A security has a beta of 0.5. If the market increases by 20%, what would you expect to happen to this security?","choices":{"A":"Increase by 40%","B":"Increase by 20%","C":"Increase by 10%","D":"Decrease by 10%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A beta of 0.5 means the security is expected to move half as much as the market. If the market increases by 20%, a security with a beta of 0.5 would be expected to increase by approximately 10% (20% x 0.5 = 10%). This lower beta indicates the security has less systematic risk than the overall market and is considered defensive.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-008","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which of the following would typically be included in an Investment Policy Statement (IPS)?","choices":{"A":"Specific stock picks and timing recommendations","B":"Investment objectives, risk tolerance, time horizon, and asset allocation guidelines","C":"Daily trading instructions","D":"Only the expected annual return"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An Investment Policy Statement (IPS) is a comprehensive document that establishes the investor's objectives and constraints. It typically includes investment objectives, risk tolerance, time horizon, liquidity needs, tax considerations, legal restrictions, and asset allocation guidelines. The IPS serves as a roadmap for investment decisions and is NOT about specific stock picks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-009","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The Sharpe ratio measures:","choices":{"A":"Total return of the portfolio","B":"Return per unit of systematic risk (beta)","C":"Risk-adjusted return relative to total risk (standard deviation)","D":"The portfolio's correlation with the market"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Sharpe ratio measures risk-adjusted return by dividing the portfolio's excess return (return minus risk-free rate) by its standard deviation (total risk). A higher Sharpe ratio indicates better risk-adjusted performance. Generally, a Sharpe ratio above 1.0 is considered acceptable, above 2.0 is very good, and above 3.0 is exceptional.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-010","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which tax-efficient strategy involves holding stock index funds in taxable accounts and bonds in tax-advantaged accounts?","choices":{"A":"Tax-loss harvesting","B":"Asset location","C":"Wash sale avoidance","D":"Constructive sale"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Asset location is a tax-efficient strategy that places tax-efficient investments (like stock index funds with low turnover and qualified dividends) in taxable accounts, while placing tax-inefficient investments (like bonds that generate ordinary income) in tax-advantaged accounts like IRAs or 401(k)s. This optimizes after-tax returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts","diversification"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-011","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"In modern portfolio theory, the efficient frontier represents:","choices":{"A":"All possible portfolios that can be constructed","B":"Portfolios offering the highest expected return for each level of risk","C":"Only portfolios containing government bonds","D":"The minimum risk portfolio available"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The efficient frontier is a key concept in modern portfolio theory representing the set of optimal portfolios that offer the highest expected return for a given level of risk, or the lowest risk for a given expected return. Portfolios that lie below the efficient frontier are suboptimal because they don't provide enough return for the level of risk taken.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-012","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A client uses the specific share identification method when selling mutual fund shares. What is the primary advantage of this approach?","choices":{"A":"It requires less record-keeping than other methods","B":"It allows the investor to minimize tax liability by selecting which shares to sell","C":"It is required by the IRS for all mutual fund sales","D":"It automatically selects the shares with the lowest cost basis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Specific share identification is the most flexible cost basis method available. It allows investors to specify exactly which shares to sell based on their anticipated tax situation, enabling them to minimize capital gains (by selling high-cost basis shares) or maximize losses for tax-loss harvesting purposes. This requires detailed record-keeping of each purchase.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["mutual-funds","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-013","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which of the following statements about Monte Carlo simulation in portfolio analysis is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"It guarantees the accuracy of future portfolio returns","B":"It generates multiple random scenarios to estimate the probability of various outcomes","C":"It only works for portfolios with no withdrawals","D":"It replaces the need for an investment policy statement"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Monte Carlo simulation is a statistical technique that generates thousands of random scenarios using defined parameters (expected returns, volatility, correlations) to estimate the probability of various portfolio outcomes. It helps evaluate whether a portfolio can meet goals given planned withdrawals. It does NOT guarantee accuracy but provides probability distributions of possible outcomes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-014","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio manager generates a return of 12% while the benchmark returns 10%. The portfolio has a beta of 1.2 and the risk-free rate is 2%. What is the portfolio's alpha?","choices":{"A":"+2.0%","B":"+0.4%","C":"-0.4%","D":"+1.6%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Alpha = Actual Return - Expected Return. Using the CAPM formula: Expected Return = Risk-free rate + Beta x (Market Return - Risk-free rate) = 2% + 1.2 x (10% - 2%) = 2% + 1.2 x 8% = 2% + 9.6% = 11.6%. Therefore, Alpha = 12% - 11.6% = +0.4%. The positive alpha indicates the manager added value beyond what was expected given the portfolio's systematic risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures","systematic-risk"]},{"id":"series7-qb-s7-port-015","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A 55-year-old client plans to retire at 65 with a goal of generating $50,000 annually from their $800,000 portfolio. Which portfolio construction consideration is MOST important for this client?","choices":{"A":"Maximizing capital appreciation through aggressive growth stocks","B":"Balancing growth for 10 more working years with income sustainability during a 25+ year retirement","C":"Investing entirely in fixed-income securities for safety","D":"Concentrating the portfolio in high-dividend stocks only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a client 10 years from retirement with a long potential retirement period (25+ years), the portfolio must balance growth (to continue building assets and outpace inflation) with the transition to income generation. A withdrawal rate of approximately 6.25% ($50,000/$800,000) is aggressive, so the portfolio needs growth to sustain withdrawals. Pure income or pure growth strategies are inappropriate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 7)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer","retirement-accounts"]}];
